# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computational-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The basis set can either be composed of atomic orbitals (yielding the linear combination of atomic orbitals approach), which is the usual choice within the quantum chemistry community; plane waves which are typically used within the solid state community, or real-space approaches.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Several types of atomic orbitals can be used: Gaussian-type orbitals, Slater-type orbitals, or numerical atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Out of the three, Gaussian-type orbitals are by far the most often used, as they allow efficient implementations of post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In modern computational chemistry, quantum chemical calculations are performed using a finite set of basis functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] When the finite basis is expanded towards an (infinite) complete set of functions, calculations using such a basis set are said to approach the complete basis set (CBS) limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In this context, *basis function* and *atomic orbital* are sometimes used interchangeably, although the basis functions are usually not true atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Within the basis set, the wavefunction is represented as a vector, the components of which correspond to coefficients of the basis functions in the linear expansion.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In such a basis, one-electron operators correspond to matrices (a.k.a. rank two tensors), whereas two-electron operators are rank four tensors.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] When molecular calculations are performed, it is common to use a basis composed of atomic orbitals, centered at each nucleus within the molecule (linear combination of atomic orbitals ansatz).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The physically best motivated basis set are Slater-type orbitals (STOs), which are solutions to the Schrödinger equation of hydrogen-like atoms, and decay exponentially far away from the nucleus.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] It can be shown that the molecular orbitals of Hartree–Fock and density-functional theory also exhibit exponential decay.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, S-type STOs also satisfy Kato's cusp condition at the nucleus, meaning that they are able to accurately describe electron density near the nucleus.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, hydrogen-like atoms lack many-electron interactions, thus the orbitals do not accurately describe electron state correlations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Unfortunately, calculating integrals with STOs is computationally difficult and it was later realized by Frank Boys that STOs could be approximated as linear combinations of Gaussian-type orbitals (GTOs) instead.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Because the product of two GTOs can be written as a linear combination of GTOs, integrals with Gaussian basis functions can be written in closed form, which leads to huge computational savings (see John Pople).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Dozens of Gaussian-type orbital basis sets have been published in the literature.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets typically come in hierarchies of increasing size, giving a controlled way to obtain more accurate solutions, however at a higher cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The smallest basis sets are called *minimal basis sets*.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set is one in which, on each atom in the molecule, a single basis function is used for each orbital in a Hartree–Fock calculation on the free atom.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For atoms such as lithium, basis functions of p type are also added to the basis functions that correspond to the 1s and 2s orbitals of the free atom, because lithium also has a 1s2p bound state.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For example, each atom in the second period of the periodic system (Li – Ne) would have a basis set of five functions (two s functions and three p functions).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set may already be exact for the gas-phase atom at the self-consistent field level of theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In the next level, additional functions are added to describe polarization of the electron density of the atom in molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] These are called **polarization functions**.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For example, while the minimal basis set for hydrogen is one function approximating the 1s atomic orbital, a simple polarized basis set typically has two s- and one p-function (which consists of three basis functions: px, py and pz).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This adds flexibility to the basis set, effectively allowing molecular orbitals involving the hydrogen atom to be more asymmetric about the hydrogen nucleus.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This is very important for modeling chemical bonding, because the bonds are often polarized.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly, d-type functions can be added to a basis set with valence p orbitals, and f-functions to a basis set with d-type orbitals, and so on.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Another common addition to basis sets is the addition of **diffuse functions**.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] These are extended Gaussian basis functions with a small exponent, which give flexibility to the "tail" portion of the atomic orbitals, far away from the nucleus.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse basis functions are important for describing anions or dipole moments, but they can also be important for accurate modeling of intra- and inter-molecular bonding.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The most common minimal basis set is STO-nG, where n is an integer.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The STO-nG basis sets are derived from a minimal Slater-type orbital basis set, with *n* representing the number of Gaussian primitive functions used to represent each Slater-type orbital.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Minimal basis sets typically give rough results that are insufficient for research-quality publication, but are much cheaper than their larger counterparts.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] There are several other minimum basis sets that have been used such as the MidiX basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] During most molecular bonding, it is the valence electrons which principally take part in the bonding.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In recognition of this fact, it is common to represent valence orbitals by more than one basis function (each of which can in turn be composed of a fixed linear combination of primitive Gaussian functions).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets in which there are multiple basis functions corresponding to each valence atomic orbital are called valence double, triple, quadruple-zeta, and so on, basis sets (zeta, ζ, was commonly used to represent the exponent of an STO basis function).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Since the different orbitals of the split have different spatial extents, the combination allows the electron density to adjust its spatial extent appropriate to the particular molecular environment.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, minimal basis sets lack the flexibility to adjust to different molecular environments.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The notation for the *split-valence* basis sets arising from the group of John Pople is typically *X-YZg*.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, *X* represents the number of primitive Gaussians comprising each core atomic orbital basis function.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The *Y* and *Z* indicate that the valence orbitals are composed of two basis functions each, the first one composed of a linear combination of *Y* primitive Gaussian functions, the other composed of a linear combination of *Z* primitive Gaussian functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, the presence of two numbers after the hyphens implies that this basis set is a *split-valence double-zeta* basis set.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Split-valence triple- and quadruple-zeta basis sets are also used, denoted as *X-YZWg*, *X-YZWVg*, etc.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Polarization functions are denoted by two different notations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The original Pople notation added "*" to indicate that all "heavy" atoms (everything but H and He) have a small set of polarization functions added to the basis (in the case of carbon, a set of 3d orbital functions).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The "**" notation indicates that all "light" atoms also receive polarization functions (this adds a set of 2p orbitals to the basis for each hydrogen atom).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Eventually it became desirable to add more polarization to the basis sets, and a new notation was developed in which the number and types of polarization functions are given explicitly in parentheses in the order (heavy,light) but with the principal quantum numbers of the orbitals implicit.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the * notation becomes (d) and the ** notation is now given as (d,p).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] If instead 3d and 4f functions were added to each heavy atom and 2p, 3p, 3d functions were added to each light atom, the notation would become (df,2pd).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In all cases, diffuse functions are indicated by either adding a + before the letter G (diffuse functions on heavy atoms only) or ++ (diffuse functions are added to all atoms).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The Pople basis sets were originally developed for use in Hartree-Fock calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Since then, correlation-consistent or polarization-consistent basis sets (see below) have been developed which are usually more appropriate for correlated wave function calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the most widely used basis sets are those developed by Dunning and coworkers, since they are designed for converging post-Hartree–Fock calculations systematically to the complete basis set limit using empirical extrapolation techniques.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For first- and second-row atoms, the basis sets are cc-pVNZ where *N* = *D*,*T*,*Q*,5,6,...
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The 'cc-p', stands for 'correlation-consistent polarized' and the 'V' indicates that only basis sets for the valence orbitals are of multiple-zeta quality.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] (Like the Pople basis sets, the core orbitals are of single-zeta quality.) They include successively larger shells of polarization (correlating) functions (*d*, *f*, *g*, etc.).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] More recently these 'correlation-consistent polarized' basis sets have become widely used and are the current state of the art for correlated or post-Hartree–Fock calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The *aug-* prefix is added if diffuse functions are included in the basis.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For period-3 atoms (Al–Ar), additional functions have turned out to be necessary; these are the cc-pV(N+d)Z basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Even larger atoms may employ pseudopotential basis sets, cc-pVNZ-PP, or relativistic-contracted Douglas-Kroll basis sets, cc-pVNZ-DK.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] While the usual Dunning basis sets are for valence-only calculations, the sets can be augmented with further functions that describe core electron correlation.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] These core-valence sets (cc-pCVXZ) can be used to approach the exact solution to the all-electron problem, and they are necessary for accurate geometric and nuclear property calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Weighted core-valence sets (cc-pwCVXZ) have also been recently suggested.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The weighted sets aim to capture core-valence correlation, while neglecting most of core-core correlation, in order to yield accurate geometries with smaller cost than the cc-pCVXZ sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse functions can also be added for describing anions and long-range interactions such as Van der Waals forces, or to perform electronic excited-state calculations, electric field property calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] A recipe for constructing additional augmented functions exists; as many as five augmented functions have been used in second hyperpolarizability calculations in the literature.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Because of the rigorous construction of these basis sets, extrapolation can be done for almost any energetic property.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, care must be taken when extrapolating energy differences as the individual energy components converge at different rates: the Hartree–Fock energy converges exponentially, whereas the correlation energy converges only polynomially.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] To understand how to get the number of functions, consider the cc-pVDZ basis set for H: There are two *s* (*L* = 0) orbitals and one *p* (*L* = 1) orbital that has 3 angular-momentum components along the *z*-axis (*m*L = −1,0,1) corresponding to *p**x*, *p**y* and *p**z*.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Thus, there are five spatial orbitals in total.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Note that each orbital can hold two electrons of opposite spin.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] As another example, Ar [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p] has 3 s orbitals (*L* = 0) and 2 sets of p orbitals (*L* = 1).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Using cc-pVDZ, orbitals are [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3s, 3p, 3p, 3d'] (where ' represents the added in polarisation orbitals), with 4 s orbitals (4 basis functions), 3 sets of p orbitals (3 × 3 = 9 basis functions), and 1 set of d orbitals (5 basis functions).
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Adding up the basis functions gives a total of 18 functions for Ar with the cc-pVDZ basis-set.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Density-functional theory has recently become widely used in computational chemistry.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, the correlation-consistent basis sets described above are suboptimal for density-functional theory, because the correlation-consistent sets have been designed for post-Hartree–Fock, while density-functional theory exhibits much more rapid basis set convergence than wave function methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Adopting a similar methodology to the correlation-consistent series, Frank Jensen introduced polarization-consistent (pc-n) basis sets as a way to quickly converge density functional theory calculations to the complete basis set limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Like the Dunning sets, the pc-n sets can be combined with basis set extrapolation techniques to obtain CBS values.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The pc-n sets can be augmented with diffuse functions to obtain augpc-n sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the various valence adaptations of Karlsruhe basis sets are briefly described below.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Gaussian-type orbital basis sets are typically optimized to reproduce the lowest possible energy for the systems used to train the basis set.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, the convergence of the energy does not imply convergence of other properties, such as nuclear magnetic shieldings, the dipole moment, or the electron momentum density, which probe different aspects of the electronic wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Manninen and Vaara have proposed completeness-optimized basis sets, where the exponents are obtained by maximization of the one-electron completeness profile instead of minimization of the energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are a way to easily approach the complete basis set limit of any property at any level of theory, and the procedure is simple to automatize.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are tailored to a specific property.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This way, the flexibility of the basis set can be focused on the computational demands of the chosen property, typically yielding much faster convergence to the complete basis set limit than is achievable with energy-optimized basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Here, only the two parameters $\alpha _{l}$ and $\beta _{l}$ must be optimized, significantly reducing the dimension of the search space or even avoiding the exponent optimization problem.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In order to properly describe electronic delocalized states, a previously optimized standard basis set can be complemented with additional delocalized Gaussian functions with small exponent values, generated by the even-tempered scheme.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This approach has also been employed to generate basis sets for other types of quantum particles rather than electrons, like quantum nuclei, negative muons or positrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In addition to localized basis sets, plane-wave basis sets can also be used in quantum-chemical simulations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Typically, the choice of the plane wave basis set is based on a cutoff energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the simulation cell that fit below the energy criterion are then included in the calculation.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] These basis sets are popular in calculations involving three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The main advantage of a plane-wave basis is that it is guaranteed to converge in a *smooth, monotonic manner* to the target wavefunction.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, when localized basis sets are used, monotonic convergence to the basis set limit may be difficult due to problems with over-completeness: in a large basis set, functions on different atoms start to look alike, and many eigenvalues of the overlap matrix approach zero.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In addition, certain integrals and operations are much easier to program and carry out with plane-wave basis functions than with their localized counterparts.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the kinetic energy operator is diagonal in the reciprocal space.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Integrals over real-space operators can be efficiently carried out using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The properties of the Fourier Transform allow a vector representing the gradient of the total energy with respect to the plane-wave coefficients to be calculated with a computational effort that scales as NPW*ln(NPW) where NPW is the number of plane-waves.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] When this property is combined with separable pseudopotentials of the Kleinman-Bylander type and pre-conditioned conjugate gradient solution techniques, the dynamic simulation of periodic problems containing hundreds of atoms becomes possible.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In practice, plane-wave basis sets are often used in combination with an 'effective core potential' or pseudopotential, so that the plane waves are only used to describe the valence charge density.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This is because core electrons tend to be concentrated very close to the atomic nuclei, resulting in large wavefunction and density gradients near the nuclei which are not easily described by a plane-wave basis set unless a very high energy cutoff, and therefore small wavelength, is used.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This combined method of a plane-wave basis set with a core pseudopotential is often abbreviated as a *PSPW* calculation.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, as all functions in the basis are mutually orthogonal and are not associated with any particular atom, plane-wave basis sets do not exhibit basis-set superposition error.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane-wave basis set is dependent on the size of the simulation cell, complicating cell size optimization.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Due to the assumption of periodic boundary conditions, plane-wave basis sets are less well suited to gas-phase calculations than localized basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Large regions of vacuum need to be added on all sides of the gas-phase molecule in order to avoid interactions with the molecule and its periodic copies.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane waves use a similar accuracy to describe the vacuum region as the region where the molecule is, meaning that obtaining the truly noninteracting limit may be computationally costly.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] A combination of some of the properties of localized basis sets and plane-wave approaches is achieved by linearized augmented-plane-wave (LAPW) basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] These are based on a partitioning of space into nonoverlapping spheres around each atom and an interstitial region in between the spheres.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] An LAPW basis function is a plane wave in the interstitial region, which is augmented by numerical atomic functions in each sphere.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The numerical atomic functions hereby provide a linearized representation of wave functions for arbitrary energies around automatically determined energy parameters.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly to plane-wave basis sets an LAPW basis set is mainly determined by a cutoff parameter for the plane-wave representation in the interstitial region.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] In the spheres the variational degrees of freedom can be extended by adding local orbitals to the basis set.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] This allows representations of wavefunctions beyond the linearized description.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the interstitial region imply three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions, though it is possible to introduce additional augmentation regions to reduce this to one or two dimensions, e.g., for the description of chain-like structures or thin films.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The atomic-like representation in the spheres allows to treat each atom with its potential singularity at the nucleus and to not rely on a pseudopotential approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The disadvantage of LAPW basis sets is its complex definition, which comes with many parameters that have to be controlled either by the user or an automatic recipe.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Another consequence of the form of the basis set are complex mathematical expressions, e.g., for the calculation of a Hamiltonian matrix or atomic forces.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space approaches offer powerful methods to solve electronic structure problems thanks to their controllable accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space basis sets can be thought to arise from the theory of interpolation, as the central idea is to represent the (unknown) orbitals in terms of some set of interpolation functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Various methods have been proposed for constructing the solution in real space, including finite elements, basis splines, Lagrange sinc-functions, and wavelets.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Finite difference algorithms are also often included in this category, even though precisely speaking, they do not form a proper basis set and are not variational unlike e.g. finite element methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] A common feature of all real-space methods is that the accuracy of the numerical basis set is improvable, so that the complete basis set limit can be reached in a systematical manner.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] For example, in finite element methods (FEMs), the wave function is represented as a linear combination of a set of piecewise polynomials.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] Lagrange interpolating polynomials (LIPs) are a commonly used basis for FEM calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The local interpolation error in LIP basis of order n is of the form $h^{n+1}\max f^{(n+1)}(\xi )$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/basis-set-chemistry] The use of high-order LIPs has been shown to be highly beneficial for accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In quantum chemistry and molecular physics, the **Born–Oppenheimer** (**BO**) **approximation** is the assumption that the wave functions of atomic nuclei and electrons in a molecule can be treated separately, based on the fact that the nuclei are much heavier than the electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Due to the larger relative mass of a nucleus compared to an electron, the coordinates of the nuclei in a system are approximated as fixed, while the coordinates of the electrons are dynamic.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The approach is named after Max Born and his 23-year-old graduate student J.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Robert Oppenheimer, the latter of whom proposed it in 1927 during a period of intense ferment in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The approximation is widely used in quantum chemistry to speed up the computation of molecular wavefunctions and other properties for large molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] There are cases where the assumption of separable motion no longer holds, which make the approximation lose validity (it is said to "break down"), but even then the approximation is usually used as a starting point for more refined methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energies $E_{\text{electronic}}$ consist of kinetic energies, interelectronic repulsions, internuclear repulsions, and electron–nuclear attractions, which are the terms typically included when computing the electronic structure of molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The benzene molecule consists of 12 nuclei and 42 electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The computational complexity, i.e., the computational power required to solve an eigenvalue equation, increases faster than the square of the number of coordinates.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] When applying the BO approximation, two smaller, consecutive steps can be used: For a given position of the nuclei, the *electronic* Schrödinger equation is solved, while treating the nuclei as stationary (not "coupled" with the dynamics of the electrons).
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This corresponding eigenvalue problem then consists only of the 126 electronic coordinates.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This electronic computation is then repeated for other possible positions of the nuclei, i.e. deformations of the molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] For benzene, this could be done using a grid of 36 possible nuclear position coordinates.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energies on this grid are then connected to give a potential energy surface for the nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This potential is then used for a second Schrödinger equation containing only the 36 coordinates of the nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In practice, the scaling of the problem is larger than $n^{2}$ , and more approximations are applied in computational chemistry to further reduce the number of variables and dimensions.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The slope of the potential energy surface can be used to simulate molecular dynamics, using it to express the mean force on the nuclei caused by the electrons and thereby skipping the calculation of the nuclear Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The BO approximation recognizes the large difference between the electron mass and the masses of atomic nuclei, and correspondingly the time scales of their motion.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Given the same amount of momentum, the nuclei move much more slowly than the electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This enables a separation of the Hamiltonian operator into electronic and nuclear terms, where cross-terms between electrons and nuclei are neglected, so that the two smaller and decoupled systems can be solved more efficiently.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In the first step, the nuclear kinetic energy is neglected, that is, the corresponding operator *T*n is subtracted from the total molecular Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In the remaining electronic Hamiltonian *H*e the nuclear positions are no longer variable, but are constant parameters (they enter the equation "parametrically").
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electron–nucleus interactions are *not* removed, i.e., the electrons still "feel" the Coulomb potential of the nuclei clamped at certain positions in space.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\chi (\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {R} )$ , the electronic wavefunction for given positions of nuclei (fixed **R**), is solved approximately.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The quantity **r** stands for all electronic coordinates and **R** for all nuclear coordinates.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energy eigenvalue *E*e depends on the chosen positions **R** of the nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Varying these positions **R** in small steps and repeatedly solving the electronic Schrödinger equation, one obtains *E*e as a function of **R**.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is the potential energy surface (PES): $E_{e}(\mathbf {R} )$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\phi (\mathbf {R} )$ is the nuclear wavefunction, is solved.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This second step of the BO approximation involves separation of vibrational, translational, and rotational motions.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This can be achieved by application of the Eckart conditions.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The eigenvalue *E* is the total energy of the molecule, including contributions from electrons, nuclear vibrations, and overall rotation and translation of the molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In accord with the Hellmann–Feynman theorem, the nuclear potential is taken to be an average over electron configurations of the sum of the electron–nuclear and internuclear electric potentials.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] It will be discussed how the BO approximation may be derived and under which conditions it is applicable.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] At the same time we will show how the BO approximation may be improved by including vibronic coupling.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] To that end the second step of the BO approximation is generalized to a set of coupled eigenvalue equations depending on nuclear coordinates only.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Off-diagonal elements in these equations are shown to be nuclear kinetic energy terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The position vectors $\mathbf {r} \equiv \{\mathbf {r} _{i}\}$ of the electrons and the position vectors $\mathbf {R} \equiv \{\mathbf {R} _{A}=(R_{Ax},R_{Ay},R_{Az})\}$ of the nuclei are with respect to a Cartesian inertial frame.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Distances between particles are written as $r_{iA}\equiv |\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} _{A}|$ (distance between electron *i* and nucleus *A*) and similar definitions hold for $r_{ij}$ and $R_{AB}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] We assume that the molecule is in a homogeneous (no external force) and isotropic (no external torque) space.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The only interactions are the two-body Coulomb interactions among the electrons and nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The Hamiltonian is expressed in atomic units, so that we do not see the Planck constant, the dielectric constant of the vacuum, electronic charge, or electronic mass in this formula.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The only constants explicitly entering the formula are *ZA* and *MA* – the atomic number and mass of nucleus *A*.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic wave functions $\chi _{k}$ will be taken to be real, which is possible when there are no magnetic or spin interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The *parametric dependence* of the functions $\chi _{k}$ on the nuclear coordinates is indicated by the symbol after the semicolon.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This indicates that, although $\chi _{k}$ is a real-valued function of $\mathbf {r}$ , its functional form depends on $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] For example, in the molecular-orbital-linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals (LCAO-MO) approximation, $\chi _{k}$ is a molecular orbital (MO) given as a linear expansion of atomic orbitals (AOs).
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] An AO depends visibly on the coordinates of an electron, but the nuclear coordinates are not explicit in the MO.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] However, upon change of geometry, i.e., change of $\mathbf {R}$ , the LCAO coefficients obtain different values and we see corresponding changes in the functional form of the MO $\chi _{k}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] and where the subscript $(\mathbf {r} )$ indicates that the integration, implied by the bra–ket notation, is over electronic coordinates only.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The matrix $\mathbb {H} _{\text{e}}(\mathbf {R} )$ is diagonal, and the nuclear Hamilton matrix is non-diagonal; its off-diagonal (*vibronic coupling*) terms ${\big (}\mathbb {H} _{\text{n}}(\mathbf {R} ){\big )}_{k'k}$ are further discussed below.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The vibronic coupling in this approach is through nuclear kinetic energy terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Solution of these coupled equations gives an approximation for energy and wavefunction that goes beyond the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Unfortunately, the off-diagonal kinetic energy terms are usually difficult to handle.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is why often a diabatic transformation is applied, which retains part of the nuclear kinetic energy terms on the diagonal, removes the kinetic energy terms from the off-diagonal and creates coupling terms between the adiabatic PESs on the off-diagonal.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] If we can neglect the off-diagonal elements the equations will uncouple and simplify drastically.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The diagonal ( $k'=k$ ) matrix elements $\langle \chi _{k}|P_{A\alpha }|\chi _{k}\rangle _{(\mathbf {r} )}$ of the operator $P_{A\alpha }$ vanish, because we assume time-reversal invariant, so $\chi _{k}$ can be chosen to be always real.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The matrix element of the one-electron operator appearing on the right side is finite.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] When the two surfaces come close, $E_{k}(\mathbf {R} )\approx E_{k'}(\mathbf {R} )$ , the nuclear momentum coupling term becomes large and is no longer negligible.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is the case where the BO approximation breaks down, and a coupled set of nuclear motion equations must be considered instead of the one equation appearing in the second step of the BO approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Conversely, if all surfaces are well separated, all off-diagonal terms can be neglected, and hence the whole matrix of $P_{\alpha }^{A}$ is effectively zero.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The third term on the right side of the expression for the matrix element of *T*n (the *Born–Oppenheimer diagonal correction*) can approximately be written as the matrix of $P_{\alpha }^{A}$ squared and, accordingly, is then negligible also.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] which are the normal second step of the BO equations discussed above.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] We reiterate that when two or more potential energy surfaces approach each other, or even cross, the Born–Oppenheimer approximation breaks down, and one must fall back on the coupled equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Usually one invokes then the diabatic approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Here $|\zeta _{n}\rangle$ are eigenfunctions of the electronic Hamiltonian assumed to form a complete Hilbert space in the given region in configuration space.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In order for this equation to yield a solution with the correct symmetry, it is suggested to apply a perturbation approach based on an elastic potential $u_{0}(\mathbf {q} )$ , which coincides with $u_{1}(\mathbf {q} )$ at the asymptotic region.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The equation with an elastic potential can be solved, in a straightforward manner, by substitution.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\Gamma$ is an arbitrary contour, and the exponential function contains the relevant symmetry as created while moving along $\Gamma$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In this equation the inhomogeneity ensures the symmetry for the perturbed part of the solution along any contour and therefore for the solution in the required region in configuration space.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The relevance of the present approach was demonstrated while studying a two-arrangement-channel model (containing one inelastic channel and one reactive channel) for which the two adiabatic states were coupled by a Jahn–Teller conical intersection.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] A nice fit between the symmetry-preserved single-state treatment and the corresponding two-state treatment was obtained.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This applies in particular to the reactive state-to-state probabilities (see Table III in Ref.
[src:computational-chemistry/born-oppenheimer-approximation] 5b), for which the ordinary BO approximation led to erroneous results, whereas the symmetry-preserving BO approximation produced the accurate results, as they followed from solving the two coupled equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The complexity inherent in the many-body problem exacerbates the challenge of providing detailed descriptions of quantum mechanical systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational results may complement information obtained by chemical experiments or predict unobserved chemical phenomena.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Building on the founding discoveries and theories in the history of quantum mechanics, the first theoretical calculations in chemistry were those of Walter Heitler and Fritz London in 1927, using valence bond theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The books that were influential in the early development of computational quantum chemistry include Linus Pauling and E.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] With the development of efficient computer technology in the 1940s, the solutions of elaborate wave equations for complex atomic systems began to be a realizable objective.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In the early 1950s, the first semi-empirical atomic orbital calculations were performed.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Theoretical chemists became extensive users of the early digital computers.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] One significant advancement was marked by Clemens C.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Roothaan's 1951 paper in the Reviews of Modern Physics.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This paper focused largely on the "LCAO MO" approach (Linear Combination of Atomic Orbitals Molecular Orbitals).
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] A very detailed account of such use in the United Kingdom is given by Smith and Sutcliffe.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The first *ab initio* Hartree–Fock method calculations on diatomic molecules were performed in 1956 at MIT, using a basis set of Slater orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For diatomic molecules, a systematic study using a minimum basis set and the first calculation with a larger basis set were published by Ransil and Nesbet respectively in 1960.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The first polyatomic calculations using Gaussian orbitals were performed in the late 1950s.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The first configuration interaction calculations were performed in Cambridge on the EDSAC computer in the 1950s using Gaussian orbitals by Boys and coworkers.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] By 1971, when a bibliography of *ab initio* calculations was published, the largest molecules included were naphthalene and azulene.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These empirical methods were replaced in the 1960s by semi-empirical methods such as CNDO.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In the early 1970s, efficient *ab initio* computer programs such as ATMOL, Gaussian, IBMOL, and POLYAYTOM, began to be used to speed *ab initio* calculations of molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Of these four programs, only Gaussian, now vastly expanded, is still in use, but many other programs are now in use.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] At the same time, the methods of molecular mechanics, such as MM2 force field, were developed, primarily by Norman Allinger.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The *Journal of Computational Chemistry* was first published in 1980.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry has featured in several Nobel Prize awards.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In 1998 the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Walter Kohn, "for his development of the density-functional theory", and John Pople, "for his development of computational methods in quantum chemistry".
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Martin Karplus, Michael Levitt and Arieh Warshel received the 2013 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "the development of multiscale models for complex chemical systems".
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These fields can give rise to several applications as shown below.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry is a tool for analyzing catalytic systems without doing experiments.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Modern electronic structure theory and density functional theory has allowed researchers to discover and understand catalysts.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational studies apply theoretical chemistry to catalysis research.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Density functional theory methods calculate the energies and orbitals of molecules to give models of those structures.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Using these methods, researchers can predict values like activation energy, site reactivity and other thermodynamic properties.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Data that is difficult to obtain experimentally can be found using computational methods to model the mechanisms of catalytic cycles.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Skilled computational chemists provide predictions that are close to experimental data with proper considerations of methods and basis sets.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] With good computational data, researchers can predict how catalysts can be improved to lower the cost and increase the efficiency of these reactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry is used in drug development to model potentially useful drug molecules and help companies save time and cost in drug development.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The drug discovery process involves analyzing data, finding ways to improve current molecules, finding synthetic routes, and testing those molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry helps with this process by giving predictions of which experiments would be best to do without conducting other experiments.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational methods can also find values that are difficult to find experimentally like pKa's of compounds.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Methods like density functional theory can be used to model drug molecules and find their properties, like their HOMO and LUMO energies and molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Aside from drug synthesis, drug carriers are also researched by computational chemists for nanomaterials.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] It allows researchers to simulate environments to test the effectiveness and stability of drug carriers.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Understanding how water interacts with these nanomaterials ensures stability of the material in human bodies.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These computational simulations help researchers optimize the material find the best way to structure these nanomaterials before making them.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Databases are useful for both computational and non computational chemists in research and verifying the validity of computational methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Empirical data is used to analyze the error of computational methods against experimental data.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Empirical data helps researchers with their methods and basis sets to have greater confidence in the researchers results.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry databases are also used in testing software or hardware for computational chemistry.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Databases can also use purely calculated data.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Purely calculated data uses calculated values over experimental values for databases.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Purely calculated data avoids dealing with these adjusting for different experimental conditions like zero-point energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These calculations can also avoid experimental errors for difficult to test molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Though purely calculated data is often not perfect, identifying issues is often easier for calculated data than experimental.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Databases also give public access to information for researchers to use.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] They contain data that other researchers have found and uploaded to these databases so that anyone can search for them.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Researchers use these databases to find information on molecules of interest and learn what can be done with those molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Some publicly available chemistry databases include the following.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The programs used in computational chemistry are based on many different quantum-chemical methods that solve the molecular Schrödinger equation associated with the molecular Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Methods that do not include any empirical or semi-empirical parameters in their equations – being derived directly from theory, with no inclusion of experimental data – are called *ab initio methods*.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Ab initio methods need to define a level of theory (the method) and a basis set.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] A basis set consists of functions centered on the molecule's atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These sets are then used to describe molecular orbitals via the linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO) molecular orbital method ansatz.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] A common type of *ab initio* electronic structure calculation is the Hartree–Fock method (HF), an extension of molecular orbital theory, where electron-electron repulsions in the molecule are not specifically taken into account; only the electrons' average effect is included in the calculation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] As the basis set size increases, the energy and wave function tend towards a limit called the Hartree–Fock limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Many types of calculations begin with a Hartree–Fock calculation and subsequently correct for electron-electron repulsion, referred to also as electronic correlation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These types of calculations are termed post–Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] By continually improving these methods, scientists can get increasingly closer to perfectly predicting the behavior of atomic and molecular systems under the framework of quantum mechanics, as defined by the Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In most cases, the Hartree–Fock wave function occupies a single configuration or determinant.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In some cases, particularly for bond-breaking processes, this is inadequate, and several configurations must be used.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The total molecular energy can be evaluated as a function of the molecular geometry; in other words, the potential energy surface.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Such a surface can be used for reaction dynamics.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The stationary points of the surface lead to predictions of different isomers and the transition structures for conversion between isomers.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] A particularly important objective, called computational thermochemistry, is to calculate thermochemical quantities such as the enthalpy of formation to chemical accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Chemical accuracy is the accuracy required to make realistic chemical predictions and is generally considered to be 1 kcal/mol or 4 kJ/mol.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] To reach that accuracy in an economic way, it is necessary to use a series of post–Hartree–Fock methods and combine the results.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These methods are called quantum chemistry composite methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In the complementary energy-dependent approach, the time-independent Schrödinger equation is solved using the scattering theory formalism.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The potential representing the interatomic interaction is given by the potential energy surfaces.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In general, the potential energy surfaces are coupled via the vibronic coupling terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] How a computational method solves quantum equations impacts the accuracy and efficiency of the method.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The split operator technique is one of these methods for solving differential equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In computational chemistry, split operator technique reduces computational costs of simulating chemical systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational costs are about how much time it takes for computers to calculate these chemical systems, as it can take days for more complex systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Quantum systems are difficult and time-consuming to solve for humans.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Split operator methods help computers calculate these systems quickly by solving the sub problems in a quantum differential equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The method does this by separating the differential equation into two different equations, like when there are more than two operators.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Once solved, the split equations are combined into one equation again to give an easily calculable solution.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This method is used in many fields that require solving differential equations, such as biology.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] However, the technique comes with a splitting error.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For example, with the following solution for a differential equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The equation can be split, but the solutions will not be exact, only similar.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This is an example of first order splitting.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] There are ways to reduce this error, which include taking an average of two split equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Another way to increase accuracy is to use higher order splitting.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Usually, second order splitting is the most that is done because higher order splitting requires much more time to calculate and is not worth the cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Higher order methods become too difficult to implement, and are not useful for solving differential equations despite the higher accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemists spend much time making systems calculated with split operator technique more accurate while minimizing the computational cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Calculating methods is a massive challenge for many chemists trying to simulate molecules or chemical environments.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Density functional theory (DFT) methods are often considered to be *ab initio methods* for determining the molecular electronic structure, even though many of the most common functionals use parameters derived from empirical data, or from more complex calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In DFT, the total energy is expressed in terms of the total one-electron density rather than the wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In this type of calculation, there is an approximate Hamiltonian and an approximate expression for the total electron density, with various different levels of approximation and accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] DFT methods can be very accurate for relatively low computational cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Some methods combine the density functional exchange functional with the Hartree–Fock exchange term and are termed hybrid functional methods, or an additional term for correlation in double-methods methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Semi-empirical quantum chemistry methods are based on the Hartree–Fock method formalism, but make many approximations and obtain some parameters from empirical data.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] They were very important in computational chemistry from the 60s to the 90s, especially for treating large molecules where the full Hartree–Fock method without the approximations were too costly.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The use of empirical parameters appears to allow some inclusion of correlation effects into the methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Primitive semi-empirical methods were designed even before, where the two-electron part of the Hamiltonian is not explicitly included.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For π-electron systems, this was the Hückel method proposed by Erich Hückel, and for all valence electron systems, the extended Hückel method proposed by Roald Hoffmann.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Sometimes, Hückel methods are referred to as "completely empirical" because they do not derive from a Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Yet, the term "empirical methods", or "empirical force fields" is usually used to describe molecular mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In many cases, large molecular systems can be modeled successfully while avoiding quantum mechanical calculations entirely.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Molecular mechanics simulations, for example, use one classical expression for the energy of a compound, for instance, the harmonic oscillator.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] All constants appearing in the equations must be obtained beforehand from experimental data or *ab initio* calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The database of compounds used for parameterization, i.e. the resulting set of parameters and functions is called the force field, is crucial to the success of molecular mechanics calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] A force field parameterized against a specific class of molecules, for instance, proteins, would be expected to only have any relevance when describing other molecules of the same class.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] These methods can be applied to proteins and other large biological molecules, and allow studies of the approach and interaction (docking) of potential drug molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Molecular dynamics (MD) use either quantum mechanics, molecular mechanics or a mixture of both to calculate forces which are then used to solve Newton's laws of motion to examine the time-dependent behavior of systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The result of a molecular dynamics simulation is a trajectory that describes how the position and velocity of particles varies with time.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The phase point of a system described by the positions and momenta of all its particles on a previous time point will determine the next phase point in time by integrating over Newton's laws of motion.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Monte Carlo (MC) generates configurations of a system by making random changes to the positions of its particles, together with their orientations and conformations where appropriate.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] It is a random sampling method, which makes use of the so-called *importance sampling*.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Importance sampling methods are able to generate low energy states, as this enables properties to be calculated accurately.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The potential energy of each configuration of the system can be calculated, together with the values of other properties, from the positions of the atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] QM/MM is a hybrid method that attempts to combine the accuracy of quantum mechanics with the speed of molecular mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] It is useful for simulating very large molecules such as enzymes.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Quantum computational chemistry aims to exploit quantum computing to simulate chemical systems, distinguishing itself from the QM/MM (Quantum Mechanics/Molecular Mechanics) approach.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] While QM/MM uses a hybrid approach, combining quantum mechanics for a portion of the system with classical mechanics for the remainder, quantum computational chemistry exclusively uses quantum computing methods to represent and process information, such as Hamiltonian operators.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Conventional computational chemistry methods often struggle with the complex quantum mechanical equations, particularly due to the exponential growth of a quantum system's wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Quantum computational chemistry addresses these challenges using quantum computing methods, such as qubitization and quantum phase estimation, which are believed to offer scalable solutions.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Qubitization involves adapting the Hamiltonian operator for more efficient processing on quantum computers, enhancing the simulation's efficiency.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Quantum phase estimation, on the other hand, assists in accurately determining energy eigenstates, which are critical for understanding the quantum system's behavior.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] While these techniques have advanced the field of computational chemistry, especially in the simulation of chemical systems, their practical application is currently limited mainly to smaller systems due to technological constraints.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Nevertheless, these developments may lead to significant progress towards achieving more precise and resource-efficient quantum chemistry simulations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The computational cost and algorithmic complexity in chemistry are used to help understand and predict chemical phenomena.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] They help determine which algorithms/computational methods to use when solving chemical problems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This section focuses on the scaling of computational complexity with molecule size and details the algorithms commonly used in both domains.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In quantum chemistry, particularly, the complexity can grow exponentially with the number of electrons involved in the system.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This exponential growth is a significant barrier to simulating large or complex systems accurately.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Advanced algorithms in both fields strive to balance accuracy with computational efficiency.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For instance, in MD, methods like Verlet integration or Beeman's algorithm are employed for their computational efficiency.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In quantum chemistry, hybrid methods combining different computational approaches (like QM/MM) are increasingly used to tackle large biomolecular systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The following list illustrates the impact of computational complexity on algorithms used in chemical computations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] While this list provides key examples, it is not comprehensive and serves as a guide to understanding how computational demands influence the selection of specific computational methods in chemistry.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Solves Newton's equations of motion for atoms and molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The standard pairwise interaction calculation in MD leads to an ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})$ complexity for N particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This is because each particle interacts with every other particle, resulting in ${\frac {N(N-1)}{2}}$ interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Advanced algorithms, such as the Ewald summation or Fast Multipole Method, reduce this to ${\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)$ or even ${\mathcal {O}}(N)$ by grouping distant particles and treating them as a single entity or using clever mathematical approximations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Combines quantum mechanical calculations for a small region with molecular mechanics for the larger environment.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The complexity of QM/MM methods depends on both the size of the quantum region and the method used for quantum calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For example, if a Hartree-Fock method is used for the quantum part, the complexity can be approximated as ${\mathcal {O}}(M^{2})$ , where M is the number of basis functions in the quantum region.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This complexity arises from the need to solve a set of coupled equations iteratively until self-consistency is achieved.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Finds a single Fock state that minimizes the energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] NP-hard or NP-complete as demonstrated by embedding instances of the Ising model into Hartree-Fock calculations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The Hartree-Fock method involves solving the Roothaan-Hall equations, which scales as ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{3})$ to ${\mathcal {O}}(N)$ depending on implementation, with N being the number of basis functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The computational cost mainly comes from evaluating and transforming the two-electron integrals.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This proof of NP-hardness or NP-completeness comes from embedding problems like the Ising model into the Hartree-Fock formalism.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Proving the complexity classes for algorithms involves a combination of mathematical proof and computational experiments.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For example, in the case of the Hartree-Fock method, the proof of NP-hardness is a theoretical result derived from complexity theory, specifically through reductions from known NP-hard problems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Investigates the electronic structure or nuclear structure of many-body systems such as atoms, molecules, and the condensed phases.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Traditional implementations of DFT typically scale as ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{3})$ , mainly due to the need to diagonalize the Kohn-Sham matrix.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The diagonalization step, which finds the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the matrix, contributes most to this scaling.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Recent advances in DFT aim to reduce this complexity through various approximations and algorithmic improvements.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] There have also been significant speed improvements in eigensolvers, in particular the ELPA solver which is used in many codes.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] CCSD and CCSD(T) methods are advanced electronic structure techniques involving single, double, and in the case of CCSD(T), perturbative triple excitations for calculating electronic correlation effects.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] CCSD scales as ${\mathcal {O}}(M^{6})$ where M is the number of basis functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This intense computational demand arises from the inclusion of single and double excitations in the electron correlation calculation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] With the addition of perturbative triples in CCSD(Tthe complexity increases to ${\mathcal {O}}(M^{7})$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This elevated complexity restricts practical usage to smaller systems, typically up to 20-25 atoms in conventional implementations.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] An adaptation of the standard CCSD(T) method using local natural orbitals (NOs) to significantly reduce the computational burden and enable application to larger systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Achieves linear scaling with the system size, a major improvement over the traditional fifth-power scaling of CCSD.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This advancement allows for practical applications to molecules of up to 100 atoms with reasonable basis sets, marking a significant step forward in computational chemistry's capability to handle larger systems with high accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemistry is not an *exact* description of real-life chemistry, as the mathematical and physical models of nature can only provide an approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] However, the majority of chemical phenomena can be described to a certain degree in a qualitative or approximate quantitative computational scheme.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Molecules consist of nuclei and electrons, so the methods of quantum mechanics apply.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Computational chemists often attempt to solve the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation, with relativistic corrections added, although some progress has been made in solving the fully relativistic Dirac equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In principle, it is possible to solve the Schrödinger equation in either its time-dependent or time-independent form, as appropriate for the problem in hand; in practice, this is not possible except for very small systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Therefore, a great number of approximate methods strive to achieve the best trade-off between accuracy and computational cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Accuracy can always be improved with greater computational cost.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Significant errors can present themselves in ab initio models comprising many electrons, due to the computational cost of full relativistic-inclusive methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] This complicates the study of molecules interacting with high atomic mass unit atoms, such as transitional metals and their catalytic properties.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Present algorithms in computational chemistry can routinely calculate the properties of small molecules that contain up to about 40 electrons with errors for energies less than a few kJ/mol.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] For geometries, bond lengths can be predicted within a few picometers and bond angles within 0.5 degrees.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] The treatment of larger molecules that contain a few dozen atoms is computationally tractable by more approximate methods such as density functional theory (DFT).
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] There is some dispute within the field whether or not the latter methods are sufficient to describe complex chemical reactions, such as those in biochemistry.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Large molecules can be studied by semi-empirical approximate methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Even larger molecules are treated by classical mechanics methods that use what are called molecular mechanics (MM).
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] In QM-MM methods, small parts of large complexes are treated quantum mechanically (QM), and the remainder is treated approximately (MM).
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Many self-sufficient computational chemistry software packages exist.
[src:computational-chemistry/computational-chemistry] Some include many methods covering a wide range, while others concentrate on a very specific range or even on one method.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] DFT has been very popular for calculations in solid-state physics since the 1970s.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] However, DFT was not considered sufficiently accurate for calculations in quantum chemistry until the 1990s, when the approximations used in the theory were greatly refined to better model the exchange and correlation interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Computational costs are relatively low when compared to traditional methods, such as exchange only Hartree–Fock theory and its descendants that include electron correlation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Since, DFT has become an important tool for methods of nuclear spectroscopy such as Mössbauer spectroscopy or perturbed angular correlation, in order to understand the origin of specific electric field gradients in crystals.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] New DFT methods have been designed to overcome this problem, by alterations to the functional or by the inclusion of additive terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical density functional theory uses a similar formalism to calculate the properties of non-uniform classical fluids.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Despite the current popularity of these alterations or of the inclusion of additional terms, they are reported to stray away from the search for the exact functional.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Further, DFT potentials obtained with adjustable parameters are no longer true DFT potentials, given that they are not functional derivatives of the exchange correlation energy with respect to the charge density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Consequently, it is not clear if the second theorem of DFT holds in such conditions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the context of computational materials science, *ab initio* (from first principles) DFT calculations allow the prediction and calculation of material behavior on the basis of quantum mechanical considerations, without requiring higher-order parameters such as fundamental material properties.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In contemporary DFT techniques the electronic structure is evaluated using a potential acting on the system's electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This DFT potential is constructed as the sum of external potentials *V*ext, which is determined solely by the structure and the elemental composition of the system, and an effective potential *V*eff, which represents interelectronic interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Thus, a problem for a representative supercell of a material with n electrons can be studied as a set of n one-electron Schrödinger-like equations, which are also known as Kohn–Sham equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Although density functional theory has its roots in the Thomas–Fermi model for the electronic structure of materials, DFT was first put on a firm theoretical footing by Walter Kohn and Pierre Hohenberg in the framework of the two **Hohenberg–Kohn theorems** (HK).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The original HK theorems held only for non-degenerate ground states in the absence of a magnetic field, although they have since been generalized to encompass these.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The first HK theorem demonstrates that the ground-state properties of a many-electron system are uniquely determined by an electron density that depends on only three spatial coordinates.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It set down the groundwork for reducing the many-body problem of N electrons with 3*N* spatial coordinates to three spatial coordinates, through the use of functionals of the electron density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This theorem has since been extended to the time-dependent domain to develop time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT), which can be used to describe excited states.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The second HK theorem defines an energy functional for the system and proves that the ground-state electron density minimizes this energy functional.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In work that later won them the Nobel prize in chemistry, the HK theorem was further developed by Walter Kohn and Lu Jeu Sham to produce Kohn–Sham DFT (KS DFT).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Within this framework, the intractable many-body problem of interacting electrons in a static external potential is reduced to a tractable problem of noninteracting electrons moving in an effective potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The effective potential includes the external potential and the effects of the Coulomb interactions between the electrons, e.g., the exchange and correlation interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Modeling the latter two interactions becomes the difficulty within KS DFT.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The simplest approximation is the local-density approximation (LDA), which is based upon exact exchange energy for a uniform electron gas, which can be obtained from the Thomas–Fermi model, and from fits to the correlation energy for a uniform electron gas.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Non-interacting systems are relatively easy to solve, as the wavefunction can be represented as a Slater determinant of orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Further, the kinetic energy functional of such a system is known exactly.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The exchange–correlation part of the total energy functional remains unknown and must be approximated.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Another approach, less popular than KS DFT but arguably more closely related to the spirit of the original HK theorems, is orbital-free density functional theory (OFDFT), in which approximate functionals are also used for the kinetic energy of the noninteracting system.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] As usual in many-body electronic structure calculations, the nuclei of the treated molecules or clusters are seen as fixed (the Born–Oppenheimer approximation), generating a static external potential V, in which the electrons are moving.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where, for the N-electron system, Ĥ is the Hamiltonian, E is the total energy, ${\hat {T}}$ is the kinetic energy, ${\hat {V}}$ is the potential energy from the external field due to positively charged nuclei, and Û is the electron–electron interaction energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The operators ${\hat {T}}$ and Û are called universal operators, as they are the same for any N-electron system, while ${\hat {V}}$ is system-dependent.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This complicated many-particle equation is not separable into simpler single-particle equations because of the interaction term Û.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] There are many sophisticated methods for solving the many-body Schrödinger equation based on the expansion of the wavefunction in Slater determinants.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] While the simplest one is the Hartree–Fock method, more sophisticated approaches are usually categorized as post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] However, the problem with these methods is the huge computational effort, which makes it virtually impossible to apply them efficiently to larger, more complex systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Here DFT provides an appealing alternative, being much more versatile, as it provides a way to systematically map the many-body problem, with Û, onto a single-body problem without Û.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This relation can be reversed, i.e., for a given ground-state density *n*0(**r**) it is possible, in principle, to calculate the corresponding ground-state wavefunction Ψ0(**r**1, …, **r***N*).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The functionals *T*[*n*] and *U*[*n*] are called universal functionals, while *V*[*n*] is called a non-universal functional, as it depends on the system under study.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] with respect to *n*(**r**), assuming one has reliable expressions for *T*[*n*] and *U*[*n*].
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A successful minimization of the energy functional will yield the ground-state density *n*0 and thus all other ground-state observables.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The variational problems of minimizing the energy functional *E*[*n*] can be solved by applying the Lagrangian method of undetermined multipliers.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where ${\hat {T}}$ denotes the kinetic-energy operator, and ${\hat {V}}_{\text{s}}$ is an effective potential in which the particles are moving.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where $V(\mathbf {r} )$ is the external potential, the second term is the Hartree term describing the electron–electron Coulomb repulsion, and the last term *V*XC is the exchange–correlation potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Here, *V*XC includes all the many-particle interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Since the Hartree term and *V*XC depend on *n*(**r**), which depends on the φi, which in turn depend on *V*s, the problem of solving the Kohn–Sham equation has to be done in a self-consistent (i.e., iterative) way.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Usually one starts with an initial guess for *n*(**r**), then calculates the corresponding *V*s and solves the Kohn–Sham equations for the φi.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] From these one calculates a new density and starts again.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This procedure is then repeated until convergence is reached.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A non-iterative approximate formulation called Harris functional DFT is an alternative approach to this.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It is possible to extend the DFT idea to the case of the Green function G instead of the density n.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It is called as Luttinger–Ward functional (or kinds of similar functionals), written as *E*[*G*].
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] However, G is determined not as its minimum, but as its extremum.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Thus we may have some theoretical and practical difficulties.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] There is no one-to-one correspondence between one-body density matrix *n*(**r**, **r**′) and the one-body potential *V*(**r**, **r**′).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] (All the eigenvalues of *n*(**r**, **r**′) are 1.) In other words, it ends up with a theory similar to the Hartree–Fock (or hybrid) theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The same theorems can be proven in the case of relativistic electrons, thereby providing generalization of DFT for the relativistic case.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Unlike the nonrelativistic theory, in the relativistic case it is possible to derive a few exact and explicit formulas for the relativistic density functional.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Let one consider an electron in the hydrogen-like ion obeying the relativistic Dirac equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where Ψ = (Ψ(1), Ψ(2), Ψ(3), Ψ(4))T is a four-component wavefunction, and E is the associated eigenenergy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It is easy to see that both of the above formulae represent density functionals.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The former formula can be easily generalized for the multi-electron case.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] One may observe that both of the functionals written above do not have extremals, of course, if a reasonably wide set of functions is allowed for variation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Nevertheless, it is possible to design a density functional with desired extremal properties out of those ones.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where *ne* in Kronecker delta symbol of the second term denotes any extremal for the functional represented by the first term of the functional F.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The second term amounts to zero for any function that is not an extremal for the first term of functional F.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] To proceed further we'd like to find Lagrange equation for this functional.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where *A* = *mc*2∫ *ne* d*τ*, and *B* = √*m*2*c*4 + *emc*2∫*Vne* d*τ*, and *V*(*τ*0) is a value of potential at some point, specified by support of variation function *δn*, which is supposed to be infinitesimal.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Apparently, this equation could have solution only if *A* = *B*.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Solutions of this equation represent extremals for functional F.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It's easy to see that all real densities, that is, densities corresponding to the bound states of the system in question, are solutions of written above equation, which could be called the Kohn–Sham equation in this particular case.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Looking back onto the definition of the functional F, we clearly see that the functional produces energy of the system for appropriate density, because the first term amounts to zero for such density and the second one delivers the energy value.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The major problem with DFT is that the exact functionals for exchange and correlation are not known, except for the free-electron gas.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] However, approximations exist which permit the calculation of certain physical quantities quite accurately.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In LDA, the exchange–correlation energy is typically separated into the exchange part and the correlation part: *ε*XC = *ε*X + *ε*C.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The exchange part is called the Dirac (or sometimes Slater) exchange, which takes the form *ε*X ∝ *n*1/3.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] There are, however, many mathematical forms for the correlation part.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Highly accurate formulae for the correlation energy density *ε*C(*n*↑, *n*↓) have been constructed from quantum Monte Carlo simulations of jellium.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Although unrelated to the Monte Carlo simulation, the two variants provide comparable accuracy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The LDA assumes that the density is the same everywhere.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Because of this, the LDA has a tendency to underestimate the exchange energy and over-estimate the correlation energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The errors due to the exchange and correlation parts tend to compensate each other to a certain degree.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] To correct for this tendency, it is common to expand in terms of the gradient of the density in order to account for the non-homogeneity of the true electron density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This allows corrections based on the changes in density away from the coordinate.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Using the latter (GGA), very good results for molecular geometries and ground-state energies have been achieved.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Potentially more accurate than the GGA functionals are the meta-GGA functionals, a natural development after the GGA (generalized gradient approximation).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Meta-GGA DFT functional in its original form includes the second derivative of the electron density (the Laplacian), whereas GGA includes only the density and its first derivative in the exchange–correlation potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Functionals of this type are, for example, TPSS and the Minnesota Functionals.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] These functionals include a further term in the expansion, depending on the density, the gradient of the density and the Laplacian (second derivative) of the density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Difficulties in expressing the exchange part of the energy can be relieved by including a component of the exact exchange energy calculated from Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Functionals of this type are known as hybrid functionals.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The DFT formalism described above breaks down, to various degrees, in the presence of a vector potential, i.e. a magnetic field.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In such a situation, the one-to-one mapping between the ground-state electron density and wavefunction is lost.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Generalizations to include the effects of magnetic fields have led to two theories: current density functional theory (CDFT) and magnetic field density functional theory (BDFT).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In both these theories, the functional used for the exchange and correlation must be generalized to include more than just the electron density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In current density functional theory, developed by Vignale and Rasolt, the functionals become dependent on both the electron density and the paramagnetic current density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In magnetic field density functional theory, developed by Salsbury, Grayce and Harris, the functionals depend on the electron density and the magnetic field, and the functional form can depend on the form of the magnetic field.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In both of these theories it has been difficult to develop functionals beyond their equivalent to LDA, which are also readily implementable computationally.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In general, density functional theory finds increasingly broad application in chemistry and materials science for the interpretation and prediction of complex system behavior at an atomic scale.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Specifically, DFT computational methods are applied for synthesis-related systems and processing parameters.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In such systems, experimental studies are often encumbered by inconsistent results and non-equilibrium conditions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Examples of contemporary DFT applications include studying the effects of dopants on phase transformation behavior in oxides, magnetic behavior in dilute magnetic semiconductor materials, and the study of magnetic and electronic behavior in ferroelectrics and dilute magnetic semiconductors.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It has also been shown that DFT gives good results in the prediction of sensitivity of some nanostructures to environmental pollutants like sulfur dioxide or acrolein, as well as prediction of mechanical properties.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In practice, Kohn–Sham theory can be applied in several distinct ways, depending on what is being investigated.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In solid-state calculations, the local density approximations are still commonly used along with plane-wave basis sets, as an electron-gas approach is more appropriate for electrons delocalised through an infinite solid.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In molecular calculations, however, more sophisticated functionals are needed, and a huge variety of exchange–correlation functionals have been developed for chemical applications.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Some of these are inconsistent with the uniform electron-gas approximation; however, they must reduce to LDA in the electron-gas limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the chemistry community, one popular functional is known as BLYP (from the name Becke for the exchange part and Lee, Yang and Parr for the correlation part).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Even more widely used is B3LYP, which is a hybrid functional in which the exchange energy, in this case from Becke's exchange functional, is combined with the exact energy from Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Along with the component exchange and correlation functionals, three parameters define the hybrid functional, specifying how much of the exact exchange is mixed in.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The adjustable parameters in hybrid functionals are generally fitted to a "training set" of molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Although the results obtained with these functionals are usually sufficiently accurate for most applications, there is no systematic way of improving them (in contrast to some of the traditional wavefunction-based methods like configuration interaction or coupled cluster theory).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the current DFT approach it is not possible to estimate the error of the calculations without comparing them to other methods or experiments.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Density functional theory is generally highly accurate but highly computationally-expensive.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] DFT has been used with machine learning techniques – especially graph neural networks – to create machine learning potentials.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] These graph neural networks approximate DFT, with the aim of achieving similar accuracies with much less computation, and are especially beneficial for large systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] They are trained using DFT-calculated properties of a known set of molecules.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The predecessor to density functional theory was the **Thomas–Fermi model**, developed independently by both Llewellyn Thomas and Enrico Fermi in 1927.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] They used a statistical model to approximate the distribution of electrons in an atom.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The mathematical basis postulated that electrons are distributed uniformly in phase space with two electrons in every $h^{3}$ of volume.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] As such, they were able to calculate the energy of an atom using this kinetic-energy functional combined with the classical expressions for the nucleus–electron and electron–electron interactions (which can both also be represented in terms of the electron density).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Although this was an important first step, the Thomas–Fermi equation's accuracy is limited because the resulting kinetic-energy functional is only approximate, and because the method does not attempt to represent the exchange energy of an atom as a conclusion of the Pauli principle.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] An exchange-energy functional was added by Paul Dirac in 1928.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] However, the Thomas–Fermi–Dirac theory remained rather inaccurate for most applications.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The largest source of error was in the representation of the kinetic energy, followed by the errors in the exchange energy, and due to the complete neglect of electron correlation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Edward Teller (1962) showed that Thomas–Fermi theory cannot describe molecular bonding.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This can be overcome by improving the kinetic-energy functional.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The Hohenberg–Kohn theorems relate to any system consisting of electrons moving under the influence of an external potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] the ground-state density uniquely determines the potential and thus all properties of the system, including the many-body wavefunction.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] , is a universal functional of the density (not depending explicitly on the external potential).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In light of the fact that the sum of the occupied energies provides the energy content of the Hamiltonian, a unique functional of the ground state charge density, the spectrum of the Hamiltonian is also a unique functional of the ground state charge density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In other words, the energy content of the Hamiltonian reaches its absolute minimum, i.e., the ground state, when the charge density is that of the ground state.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] is then the ground-state energy of this system.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The many-electron Schrödinger equation can be very much simplified if electrons are divided in two groups: valence electrons and inner core electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The electrons in the inner shells are strongly bound and do not play a significant role in the chemical binding of atoms; they also partially screen the nucleus, thus forming with the nucleus an almost inert core.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Binding properties are almost completely due to the valence electrons, especially in metals and semiconductors.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This separation suggests that inner electrons can be ignored in a large number of cases, thereby reducing the atom to an ionic core that interacts with the valence electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The use of an effective interaction, a pseudopotential, that approximates the potential felt by the valence electrons, was first proposed by Fermi in 1934 and Hellmann in 1935.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In spite of the simplification pseudo-potentials introduce in calculations, they remained forgotten until the late 1950s.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A crucial step toward more realistic pseudo-potentials was given by William C.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Topp and John Hopfield, who suggested that the pseudo-potential should be adjusted such that they describe the valence charge density accurately.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Based on that idea, modern pseudo-potentials are obtained inverting the free-atom Schrödinger equation for a given reference electronic configuration and forcing the pseudo-wavefunctions to coincide with the true valence wavefunctions beyond a certain distance rℓ.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] where *Rl*(*r*) is the radial part of the wavefunction with angular momentum ℓ, and PP and AE denote the pseudo-wavefunction and the true (all-electron) wavefunction respectively.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The index n in the true wavefunctions denotes the valence level.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The distance rℓ beyond which the true and the pseudo-wavefunctions are equal is also dependent on ℓ.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The electrons of a system will occupy the lowest Kohn–Sham eigenstates up to a given energy level according to the Aufbau principle.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] This corresponds to the steplike Fermi–Dirac distribution at absolute zero.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] If there are several degenerate or close to degenerate eigenstates at the Fermi level, it is possible to get convergence problems, since very small perturbations may change the electron occupation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] One way of damping these oscillations is to *smear* the electrons, i.e. allowing fractional occupancies.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] One approach of doing this is to assign a finite temperature to the electron Fermi–Dirac distribution.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Other ways is to assign a cumulative Gaussian distribution of the electrons or using a Methfessel–Paxton method.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical density functional theory is a classical statistical method to investigate the properties of many-body systems consisting of interacting molecules, macromolecules, nanoparticles or microparticles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The classical non-relativistic method is correct for classical fluids with particle velocities less than the speed of light and thermal de Broglie wavelength smaller than the distance between particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The theory is based on the calculus of variations of a thermodynamic functional, which is a function of the spatially dependent density function of particles, thus the name.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The same name is used for quantum DFT, which is the theory to calculate the electronic structure of electrons based on spatially dependent electron density with quantum and relativistic effects.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is a popular and useful method to study fluid phase transitions, ordering in complex liquids, physical characteristics of interfaces and nanomaterials.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Since the 1970s it has been applied to the fields of materials science, biophysics, chemical engineering and civil engineering.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Computational costs are much lower than for molecular dynamics simulations, which provide similar data and a more detailed description but are limited to small systems and short time scales.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is valuable to interpret and test numerical results and to define trends although details of the precise motion of the particles are lost due to averaging over all possible particle trajectories.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] As in electronic systems, there are fundamental and numerical difficulties in using DFT to quantitatively describe the effect of intermolecular interaction on structure, correlations and thermodynamic properties.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT addresses the difficulty of describing thermodynamic equilibrium states of many-particle systems with nonuniform density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT has its roots in theories such as the van der Waals theory for the equation of state and the virial expansion method for the pressure.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In order to account for correlation in the positions of particles the direct correlation function was introduced as the effective interaction between two particles in the presence of a number of surrounding particles by Leonard Ornstein and Frits Zernike in 1914.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The connection to the density pair distribution function was given by the Ornstein–Zernike equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The importance of correlation for thermodynamic properties was explored through density distribution functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative was introduced to define the distribution functions of classical mechanical systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Theories were developed for simple and complex liquids using the ideal gas as a basis for the free energy and adding molecular forces as a second-order perturbation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A term in the gradient of the density was added to account for non-uniformity in density in the presence of external fields or surfaces.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] These theories can be considered precursors of DFT.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] To develop a formalism for the statistical thermodynamics of non-uniform fluids functional differentiation was used extensively by Percus and Lebowitz (1961), which led to the Percus–Yevick equation linking the density distribution function and the direct correlation.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Other closure relations were also proposed;the Classical-map hypernetted-chain method, the BBGKY hierarchy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the late 1970s classical DFT was applied to the liquid–vapor interface and the calculation of surface tension.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Other applications followed: the freezing of simple fluids, formation of the glass phase, the crystal–melt interface and dislocation in crystals, properties of polymer systems, and liquid crystal ordering.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT was applied to colloid dispersions, which were discovered to be good models for atomic systems.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] By assuming local chemical equilibrium and using the local chemical potential of the fluid from DFT as the driving force in fluid transport equations, equilibrium DFT is extended to describe non-equilibrium phenomena and fluid dynamics on small scales.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT allows the calculation of the equilibrium particle density and prediction of thermodynamic properties and behavior of a many-body system on the basis of model interactions between particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The spatially dependent density determines the local structure and composition of the material.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It is determined as a function that optimizes the thermodynamic potential of the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The grand potential is evaluated as the sum of the ideal-gas term with the contribution from external fields and an excess thermodynamic free energy arising from interparticle interactions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the simplest approach the excess free-energy term is expanded on a system of uniform density using a functional Taylor expansion.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The excess free energy is then a sum of the contributions from *s*-body interactions with density-dependent effective potentials representing the interactions between *s* particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In most calculations the terms in the interactions of three or more particles are neglected (second-order DFT).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] When the structure of the system to be studied is not well approximated by a low-order perturbation expansion with a uniform phase as the zero-order term, non-perturbative free-energy functionals have also been developed.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The minimization of the grand potential functional in arbitrary local density functions for fixed chemical potential, volume and temperature provides self-consistent thermodynamic equilibrium conditions, in particular, for the local chemical potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The functional is not in general a convex functional of the density; solutions may not be local minima.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Limiting to low-order corrections in the local density is a well-known problem, although the results agree (reasonably) well on comparison to experiment.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A variational principle is used to determine the equilibrium density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] It can be shown that for constant temperature and volume the correct equilibrium density minimizes the grand potential functional $\Omega$ of the grand canonical ensemble over density functions $n(\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The Helmholtz free energy functional F is defined as $F=\Omega +\int d^{3}\mathbf {r} \,n(\mathbf {r} )\mu (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative in the density function determines the local chemical potential: $\mu (\mathbf {r} )=\delta F(\mathbf {r} )/\delta n(\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In classical statistical mechanics the partition function is a sum over probability for a given microstate of N classical particles as measured by the Boltzmann factor in the Hamiltonian of the system.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The Hamiltonian splits into kinetic and potential energy, which includes interactions between particles, as well as external potentials.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The partition function of the grand canonical ensemble defines the grand potential.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] A correlation function is introduced to describe the effective interaction between particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The *s*-body density distribution function is defined as the statistical ensemble average $\langle \dots \rangle$ of particle positions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The radial distribution function with *s* = 2 measures the change in the density at a given point for a change of the local chemical interaction at a distant point.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In a fluid the free energy is a sum of the ideal free energy and the excess free-energy contribution $\Delta F$ from interactions between particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The one-body direct correlation function plays the role of an effective mean field.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative in density of the one-body direct correlation results in the direct correlation function between two particles $c_{2}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The direct correlation function is the correlation contribution to the change of local chemical potential at a point $\mathbf {r}$ for a density change at $\mathbf {r} '$ and is related to the work of creating density changes at various positions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In dilute gases the direct correlation function is simply the pair-wise interaction between particles (Debye–Huckel equation).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Various assumptions and approximations adapted to the system under study lead to expressions for the free energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Correlation functions are used to calculate the free-energy functional as an expansion on a known reference system.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] If the non-uniform fluid can be described by a density distribution that is not far from uniform density a functional Taylor expansion of the free energy in density increments leads to an expression for the thermodynamic potential using known correlation functions of the uniform system.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In the square gradient approximation a strong non-uniform density contributes a term in the gradient of the density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In a perturbation theory approach the direct correlation function is given by the sum of the direct correlation in a known system such as hard spheres and a term in a weak interaction such as the long range London dispersion force.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] In a local density approximation the local excess free energy is calculated from the effective interactions with particles distributed at uniform density of the fluid in a cell surrounding a particle.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Other improvements have been suggested such as the weighted density approximation for a direct correlation function of a uniform system which distributes the neighboring particles with an effective weighted density calculated from a self-consistent condition on the direct correlation function.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The variational Mermin principle leads to an equation for the equilibrium density and system properties are calculated from the solution for the density.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The equation is a non-linear integro-differential equation and finding a solution is not trivial, requiring numerical methods, except for the simplest models.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is supported by standard software packages, and specific software is currently under development.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Assumptions can be made to propose trial functions as solutions, and the free energy is expressed in the trial functions and optimized with respect to parameters of the trial functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] Examples are a localized Gaussian function centered on crystal lattice points for the density in a solid, the hyperbolic function $\tanh(r)$ for interfacial density profiles.
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] The extension of classical DFT towards nonequilibrium systems is known as dynamical density functional theory (DDFT).
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] with the mobility $\Gamma$ and the free energy F .
[src:computational-chemistry/density-functional-theory] For a system of noninteracting particles, DDFT reduces to the standard diffusion equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In computational physics and chemistry, the **Hartree–Fock (HF) method** is used for approximating the wave function and the energy of a quantum many-body system in a stationary state.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] It is named after Douglas Hartree and Vladimir Fock.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method often assumes that the exact N -body wave function of the system can be approximated by a single Slater determinant (in the case where the particles are fermions) or by a single permanent (in the case of bosons) of N spin-orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] By invoking the variational method, one can derive a set of N coupled equations for the N spin orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] A solution of these equations yields the Hartree–Fock wave function and energy of the system.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Hartree–Fock approximation is an instance of mean-field theory, where neglecting higher-order fluctuations in order parameter allows interaction terms to be replaced with quadratic terms, obtaining exactly solvable Hamiltonians.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Especially in the older literature, the Hartree–Fock method is also called the **self-consistent field method** (**SCF**).
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In deriving what is now called the Hartree equation as an approximate solution of the Schrödinger equation, Hartree required the final field as computed from the charge distribution to be "self-consistent" with the assumed initial field.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Thus, self-consistency was a requirement of the solution.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The solutions to the non-linear Hartree–Fock equations also behave as if each particle is subjected to the mean field created by all other particles (see the Fock operator below), and hence the terminology continued.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The equations are almost universally solved by means of an iterative method, although the fixed-point iteration algorithm does not always converge.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] This solution scheme is not the only one possible and is not an essential feature of the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method finds its typical application in the solution of the Schrödinger equation for atoms, molecules, nanostructures and solids but it has also found widespread use in nuclear physics.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] (See Hartree–Fock–Bogoliubov method for a discussion of its application in nuclear structure theory).
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] For both atoms and molecules, the Hartree–Fock solution is the central starting point for most methods that describe the many-electron system more accurately.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The rest of this article will focus on applications in electronic structure theory suitable for molecules with the atom as a special case.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The discussion here is only for the restricted Hartree–Fock method, where the atom or molecule is a closed-shell system with all orbitals (atomic or molecular) doubly occupied.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Open-shell systems, where some of the electrons are not paired, can be dealt with by either the restricted open-shell or the unrestricted Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The origin of the Hartree–Fock method dates back to the end of the 1920s, soon after the discovery of the Schrödinger equation in 1926.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Douglas Hartree's methods were guided by some earlier, semi-empirical methods of the early 1920s (by E.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Lindsay, and himself) set in the old quantum theory of Bohr.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In the Bohr model of the atom, the energy of a state with principal quantum number *n* is given in atomic units as $E=-1/n^{2}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] It was observed from atomic spectra that the energy levels of many-electron atoms are well described by applying a modified version of Bohr's formula.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The existence of a non-zero quantum defect was attributed to electron–electron repulsion, which clearly does not exist in the isolated hydrogen atom.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] This repulsion resulted in partial screening of the bare nuclear charge.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] These early researchers later introduced other potentials containing additional empirical parameters with the hope of better reproducing the experimental data.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Hartree introduced a procedure, which he called the self-consistent field method, to calculate approximate wave functions and energies for atoms and ions.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Hartree sought to do away with empirical parameters and solve the many-body time-independent Schrödinger equation from fundamental physical principles, i.e., ab initio.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] His first proposed method of solution became known as the *Hartree method*, or *Hartree product*.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] However, many of Hartree's contemporaries did not understand the physical reasoning behind the Hartree method: it appeared to many people to contain empirical elements, and its connection to the solution of the many-body Schrödinger equation was unclear.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Gaunt independently showed that the Hartree method could be couched on a sounder theoretical basis by applying the variational principle to an ansatz (trial wave function) as a product of single-particle functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Fock independently pointed out that the Hartree method did not respect the principle of antisymmetry of the wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree method used the Pauli exclusion principle in its older formulation, forbidding the presence of two electrons in the same quantum state.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] However, this was shown to be fundamentally incomplete in its neglect of quantum statistics.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The original Hartree method can then be viewed as an approximation to the Hartree–Fock method by neglecting exchange.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Fock's original method relied heavily on group theory and was too abstract for contemporary physicists to understand and implement.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In 1935, Hartree reformulated the method to be more suitable for the purposes of calculation.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method, despite its physically more accurate picture, was little used until the advent of electronic computers in the 1950s due to the much greater computational demands over the early Hartree method and empirical models.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Initially, both the Hartree method and the Hartree–Fock method were applied exclusively to atoms, where the spherical symmetry of the system allowed one to greatly simplify the problem.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] These approximate methods were (and are) often used together with the central field approximation to impose the condition that electrons in the same shell have the same radial part and to restrict the variational solution to be a spin eigenfunction.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Even so, calculating a solution by hand using the Hartree–Fock equations for a medium-sized atom was laborious; small molecules required computational resources far beyond what was available before 1950.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock method is typically used to solve the time-independent Schrödinger equation for a multi-electron atom or molecule as described in the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Since there are no known analytic solutions for many-electron systems (there *are* solutions for one-electron systems such as hydrogenic atoms and the diatomic hydrogen cation), the problem is solved numerically.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Relaxation of the last two approximations give rise to many so-called post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The variational theorem states that for a time-independent Hamiltonian operator, any trial wave function will have an energy expectation value that is greater than or equal to the true ground-state wave function corresponding to the given Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Because of this, the Hartree–Fock energy is an upper bound to the true ground-state energy of a given molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In the context of the Hartree–Fock method, the best possible solution is at the *Hartree–Fock limit*; i.e., the limit of the Hartree–Fock energy as the basis set approaches completeness.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] (The other is the *full-CI limit*, where the last two approximations of the Hartree–Fock theory as described above are completely undone.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] It is only when both limits are attained that the exact solution, up to the Born–Oppenheimer approximation, is obtained.) The Hartree–Fock energy is the minimal energy for a single Slater determinant.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The starting point for the Hartree–Fock method is a set of approximate one-electron wave functions known as *spin-orbitals*.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] For an atomic orbital calculation, these are typically the orbitals for a hydrogen-like atom (an atom with only one electron, but the appropriate nuclear charge).
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] For a molecular orbital or crystalline calculation, the initial approximate one-electron wave functions are typically a linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO).
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The orbitals above only account for the presence of other electrons in an average manner.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In the Hartree–Fock method, the effect of other electrons are accounted for in a mean-field theory context.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The orbitals are optimized by requiring them to minimize the energy of the respective Slater determinant.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The resultant variational conditions on the orbitals lead to a new one-electron operator, the Fock operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] At the minimum, the occupied orbitals are eigensolutions to the Fock operator via a unitary transformation between themselves.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Fock operator is an effective one-electron Hamiltonian operator being the sum of two terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The first is a sum of kinetic-energy operators for each electron, the internuclear repulsion energy, and a sum of nuclear–electronic Coulombic attraction terms.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The second are Coulombic repulsion terms between electrons in a mean-field theory description; a net repulsion energy for each electron in the system, which is calculated by treating all of the other electrons within the molecule as a smooth distribution of negative charge.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] This is the major simplification inherent in the Hartree–Fock method and is equivalent to the fifth simplification in the above list.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Since the Fock operator depends on the orbitals used to construct the corresponding Fock matrix, the eigenfunctions of the Fock operator are in turn new orbitals, which can be used to construct a new Fock operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In this way, the Hartree–Fock orbitals are optimized iteratively until the change in total electronic energy falls below a predefined threshold.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In this way, a set of self-consistent one-electron orbitals is calculated.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The Hartree–Fock electronic wave function is then the Slater determinant constructed from these orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Following the basic postulates of quantum mechanics, the Hartree–Fock wave function can then be used to compute any desired chemical or physical property within the framework of the Hartree–Fock method and the approximations employed.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] To derive the Hartree-Fock equation we minimize the energy functional for N electrons with orthonormal constraints.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] We choose a basis set $\phi _{i}(x_{i})$ in which the Lagrange multiplier matrix $\lambda _{ij}$ becomes diagonal, i.e. $\lambda _{ij}=\epsilon _{i}\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The factor 1/2 before the double integrals in the molecular Hamiltonian drops out due to symmetry and the product rule.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The exchange operator has no classical analogue and can only be defined as an integral operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The solution $\phi _{k}$ and $\epsilon _{k}$ are called molecular orbital and orbital energy respectively.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Although Hartree-Fock equation appears in the form of a eigenvalue problem, the Fock operator itself depends on $\phi$ and must be solved by a different technique.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The general optimal total energy $E_{HF}$ can be written in terms of spin orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] where i and j index spin orbitals, ${\hat {J}}_{ij}$ and ${\hat {K}}_{ij}$ are matrix elements of the Coulomb and exchange operators respectively, and $V_{\text{nucl}}$ is the total electrostatic repulsion between all the nuclei in the molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] The total energy is not simply equal to the sum of orbital energies.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] where i and j now index spatial orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Typically, in modern Hartree–Fock calculations, the one-electron wave functions are approximated by a linear combination of atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] These atomic orbitals are called Slater-type orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Furthermore, it is very common for the "atomic orbitals" in use to actually be composed of a linear combination of one or more Gaussian-type orbitals, rather than Slater-type orbitals, in the interests of saving large amounts of computation time.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Various basis sets are used in practice, most of which are composed of Gaussian functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In some applications, an orthogonalization method such as the Gram–Schmidt process is performed in order to produce a set of orthogonal basis functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] This can in principle save computational time when the computer is solving the Roothaan–Hall equations by converting the overlap matrix effectively to an identity matrix.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Numerical stability can be a problem with this procedure and there are various ways of combatting this instability.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] One of the most basic and generally applicable is called *F-mixing* or damping.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] With F-mixing, once a single-electron wave function is calculated, it is not used directly.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Instead, some combination of that calculated wave function and the previous wave functions for that electron is used, the most common being a simple linear combination of the calculated and immediately preceding wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] A clever dodge, employed by Hartree, for atomic calculations was to increase the nuclear charge, thus pulling all the electrons closer together.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] As the system stabilised, this was gradually reduced to the correct charge.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] In molecular calculations a similar approach is sometimes used by first calculating the wave function for a positive ion and then to use these orbitals as the starting point for the neutral molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Modern molecular Hartree–Fock computer programs use a variety of methods to ensure convergence of the Roothaan–Hall equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Of the five simplifications outlined in the section "Hartree–Fock algorithm", the fifth is typically the most important.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Neglect of electron correlation can lead to large deviations from experimental results.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] A number of approaches to this weakness, collectively called post-Hartree–Fock methods, have been devised to include electron correlation to the multi-electron wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] One of these approaches, Møller–Plesset perturbation theory, treats correlation as a perturbation of the Fock operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Others expand the true multi-electron wave function in terms of a linear combination of Slater determinants—such as multi-configurational self-consistent field, configuration interaction, quadratic configuration interaction, and complete active space SCF (CASSCF).
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Still others (such as variational quantum Monte Carlo) modify the Hartree–Fock wave function by multiplying it by a correlation function ("Jastrow" factor), a term which is explicitly a function of multiple electrons that cannot be decomposed into independent single-particle functions.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] An alternative to Hartree–Fock calculations used in some cases is density functional theory, which treats both exchange and correlation energies, albeit approximately.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Indeed, it is common to use calculations that are a hybrid of the two methods—the popular B3LYP scheme is one such hybrid functional method.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] Another option is to use modern valence bond methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/hartree-fock-method] For a list of software packages known to handle Hartree–Fock calculations, particularly for molecules and solids, see the list of quantum chemistry and solid state physics software.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In chemistry, a **molecular orbital** is a mathematical function describing the location and wave-like behavior of an electron in a molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This function can be used to calculate chemical and physical properties such as the probability of finding an electron in any specific region.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The terms *atomic orbital* and *molecular orbital* were introduced by Robert S.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Mulliken in 1932 to mean *one-electron orbital wave functions*.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] At an elementary level, they are used to describe the *region* of space in which a function has a significant amplitude.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In an isolated atom, the orbital electrons' location is determined by functions called atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] When multiple atoms combine chemically into a molecule by forming a valence chemical bond, the electrons' locations are determined by the molecule as a whole, so the atomic orbitals combine to form molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The electrons from the constituent atoms occupy the molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Mathematically, molecular orbitals are an approximate solution to the Schrödinger equation for the electrons in the field of the molecule's atomic nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] They are usually constructed by combining atomic orbitals or hybrid orbitals from each atom of the molecule, or other molecular orbitals from groups of atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] They can be quantitatively calculated using the Hartree–Fock or self-consistent field (SCF) methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital (MO) can be used to represent the regions in a molecule where an electron occupying that orbital is likely to be found.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are approximate solutions to the Schrödinger equation for the electrons in the electric field of the molecule's atomic nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] However calculating the orbitals directly from this equation is far too intractable a problem.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Instead they are obtained from the combination of atomic orbitals, which predict the location of an electron in an atom.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital can specify the electron configuration of a molecule: the spatial distribution and energy of one (or one pair of) electron(s).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Most commonly a MO is represented as a linear combination of atomic orbitals (the LCAO-MO method), especially in qualitative or very approximate usage.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] They are invaluable in providing a simple model of bonding in molecules, understood through molecular orbital theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Most present-day methods in computational chemistry begin by calculating the MOs of the system.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital describes the behavior of one electron in the electric field generated by the nuclei and some average distribution of the other electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In the case of two electrons occupying the same orbital, the Pauli principle demands that they have opposite spin.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Necessarily this is an approximation, and highly accurate descriptions of the molecular electronic wave function do not have orbitals (see configuration interaction).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are, in general, delocalized throughout the entire molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Moreover, if the molecule has symmetry elements, its nondegenerate molecular orbitals are either symmetric or antisymmetric with respect to any of these symmetries.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In other words, the application of a symmetry operation **S** (e.g., a reflection, rotation, or inversion) to molecular orbital ψ results in the molecular orbital being unchanged or reversing its mathematical sign: **S**ψ = ±ψ.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In planar molecules, for example, molecular orbitals are either symmetric (sigma) or antisymmetric (pi) with respect to reflection in the molecular plane.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] If molecules with degenerate orbital energies are also considered, a more general statement that molecular orbitals form bases for the irreducible representations of the molecule's symmetry group holds.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In contrast to these symmetry-adapted *canonical* molecular orbitals, localized molecular orbitals can be formed by applying certain mathematical transformations to the canonical orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The advantage of this approach is that the orbitals will correspond more closely to the "bonds" of a molecule as depicted by a Lewis structure.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] As a disadvantage, the energy levels of these localized orbitals no longer have physical meaning.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] (The discussion in the rest of this article will focus on canonical molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals arise from allowed interactions between atomic orbitals, which are allowed if the symmetries (determined from group theory) of the atomic orbitals are compatible with each other.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Efficiency of atomic orbital interactions is determined from the overlap (a measure of how well two orbitals constructively interact with one another) between two atomic orbitals, which is significant if the atomic orbitals are close in energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Finally, the number of molecular orbitals formed must be equal to the number of atomic orbitals in the atoms being combined to form the molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For an imprecise, but qualitatively useful, discussion of the molecular structure, the molecular orbitals can be obtained from the "Linear combination of atomic orbitals molecular orbital method" ansatz.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Here, the molecular orbitals are expressed as linear combinations of atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals were first introduced by Friedrich Hund and Robert S.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The linear combination of atomic orbitals or "LCAO" approximation for molecular orbitals was introduced in 1929 by Sir John Lennard-Jones.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] His ground-breaking paper showed how to derive the electronic structure of the fluorine and oxygen molecules from quantum principles.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This qualitative approach to molecular orbital theory is part of the start of modern quantum chemistry.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Linear combinations of atomic orbitals (LCAO) can be used to estimate the molecular orbitals that are formed upon bonding between the molecule's constituent atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Similar to an atomic orbital, a Schrödinger equation, which describes the behavior of an electron, can be constructed for a molecular orbital as well.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Linear combinations of atomic orbitals, or the sums and differences of the atomic wavefunctions, provide approximate solutions to the Hartree–Fock equations which correspond to the independent-particle approximation of the molecular Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] where $\Psi$ and $\Psi ^{*}$ are the molecular wavefunctions for the bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals, respectively, $\psi _{a}$ and $\psi _{b}$ are the atomic wavefunctions from atoms a and b, respectively, and $c_{a}$ and $c_{b}$ are adjustable coefficients.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] These coefficients can be positive or negative, depending on the energies and symmetries of the individual atomic orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] As the two atoms become closer together, their atomic orbitals overlap to produce areas of high electron density, and, as a consequence, molecular orbitals are formed between the two atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The atoms are held together by the electrostatic attraction between the positively charged nuclei and the negatively charged electrons occupying bonding molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] When atomic orbitals interact, the resulting molecular orbital can be of three types: bonding, antibonding, or non bonding.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The type of interaction between atomic orbitals can be further categorized by the molecular-orbital symmetry labels σ (sigma), π (pi), δ (delta), φ (phi), γ (gamma) etc.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] These are the Greek letters corresponding to the atomic orbitals s, p, d, f and g respectively.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The number of nodal planes containing the internuclear axis between the atoms concerned is zero for σ MOs, one for π, two for δ, three for φ and four for γ.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A MO with σ symmetry results from the interaction of either two atomic s-orbitals or two atomic pz-orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] An MO will have σ-symmetry if the orbital is symmetric with respect to the axis joining the two nuclear centers, the internuclear axis.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This means that rotation of the MO about the internuclear axis does not result in a phase change.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A σ* orbital, sigma antibonding orbital, also maintains the same phase when rotated about the internuclear axis.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The σ* orbital has a nodal plane that is between the nuclei and perpendicular to the internuclear axis.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A MO with π symmetry results from the interaction of either two atomic px orbitals or py orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] An MO will have π symmetry if the orbital is asymmetric with respect to rotation about the internuclear axis.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This means that rotation of the MO about the internuclear axis will result in a phase change.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] There is one nodal plane containing the internuclear axis, if real orbitals are considered.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A π* orbital, pi antibonding orbital, will also produce a phase change when rotated about the internuclear axis.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The π* orbital also has a second nodal plane between the nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A MO with δ symmetry results from the interaction of two atomic dxy or dx2-y2 orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Because these molecular orbitals involve low-energy d atomic orbitals, they are seen in transition-metal complexes.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A δ bonding orbital has two nodal planes containing the internuclear axis, and a δ* antibonding orbital also has a third nodal plane between the nuclei.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Theoretical chemists have conjectured that higher-order bonds, such as phi bonds corresponding to overlap of f atomic orbitals, are possible.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] There is no known example of a molecule purported to contain a phi bond.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For molecules that possess a center of inversion (centrosymmetric molecules) there are additional labels of symmetry that can be applied to molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] If inversion through the center of symmetry in a molecule results in the same phases for the molecular orbital, then the MO is said to have gerade (g) symmetry, from the German word for even.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] If inversion through the center of symmetry in a molecule results in a phase change for the molecular orbital, then the MO is said to have ungerade (u) symmetry, from the German word for odd.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For a bonding MO with σ-symmetry, the orbital is σg (s' + s'' is symmetric), while an antibonding MO with σ-symmetry the orbital is σu, because inversion of s' – s'' is antisymmetric.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The qualitative approach of MO analysis uses a molecular orbital diagram to visualize bonding interactions in a molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In this type of diagram, the molecular orbitals are represented by horizontal lines; the higher a line the higher the energy of the orbital, and degenerate orbitals are placed on the same level with a space between them.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For more complicated molecules, the wave mechanics approach loses utility in a qualitative understanding of bonding (although is still necessary for a quantitative approach).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Arrange the SALCs of each molecular fragment in order of energy, noting first whether they stem from *s*, *p*, or *d* orbitals (and put them in the order *s* < *p* < *d*), and then their number of internuclear nodes.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Combine SALCs of the same symmetry type from the two fragments, and from N SALCs form N molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Estimate the relative energies of the molecular orbitals from considerations of overlap and relative energies of the parent orbitals, and draw the levels on a molecular orbital energy level diagram (showing the origin of the orbitals).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Confirm, correct, and revise this qualitative order by carrying out a molecular orbital calculation by using commercial software.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are said to be degenerate if they have the same energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For example, in the homonuclear diatomic molecules of the first ten elements, the molecular orbitals derived from the px and the py atomic orbitals result in two degenerate bonding orbitals (of low energy) and two degenerate antibonding orbitals (of high energy).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In an ionic bond, oppositely charged ions are bonded by electrostatic attraction.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] It is possible to describe ionic bonds with molecular orbital theory by treating them as extremely polar bonds.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Their bonding orbitals are very close in energy to the atomic orbitals of the anion.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] They are also very similar in character to the anion's atomic orbitals, which means the electrons are completely shifted to the anion.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In computer diagrams, the orbitals are centered on the anion's core.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The bond order, or number of bonds, of a molecule can be determined by combining the number of electrons in bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] A pair of electrons in a bonding orbital creates a bond, whereas a pair of electrons in an antibonding orbital negates a bond.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] For example, N2, with eight electrons in bonding orbitals and two electrons in antibonding orbitals, has a bond order of three, which constitutes a triple bond.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Bond strength is proportional to bond order—a greater amount of bonding produces a more stable bond—and bond length is inversely proportional to it—a stronger bond is shorter.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] There are rare exceptions to the requirement of molecule having a positive bond order.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Although Be2 has a bond order of 0 according to MO analysis, there is experimental evidence of a highly unstable Be2 molecule having a bond length of 245 pm and bond energy of 10 kJ/mol.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The highest occupied molecular orbital and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital are often referred to as the HOMO and LUMO, respectively.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The difference of the energies of the HOMO and LUMO is called the HOMO–LUMO gap.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This notion is often the matter of confusion in literature and should be considered with caution.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In addition, the HOMO–LUMO gap can be related to a bulk-material band gap or transport gap, which is usually much smaller than the single-molecule fundamental gap.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Homonuclear diatomic MOs contain equal contributions from each atomic orbital in the basis set.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This is shown in the homonuclear diatomic MO diagrams for H2, He2, and Li2, all of which containing symmetric orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] As a simple MO example, consider the electrons in a hydrogen molecule, H2 (see molecular orbital diagram), with the two atoms labelled H' and H".
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The lowest-energy atomic orbitals, 1s' and 1s", do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The symmetric combination (called a bonding orbital) is lower in energy than the basis orbitals, and the antisymmetric combination (called an antibonding orbital) is higher.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Because the H2 molecule has two electrons, they can both go in the bonding orbital, making the system lower in energy (hence more stable) than two free hydrogen atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The bond order is equal to the number of bonding electrons minus the number of antibonding electrons, divided by 2.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In this example, there are 2 electrons in the bonding orbital and none in the antibonding orbital; the bond order is 1, and there is a single bond between the two hydrogen atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] On the other hand, consider the hypothetical molecule of He2 with the atoms labeled He' and He".
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] As with H2, the lowest energy atomic orbitals are the 1s' and 1s", and do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule, while the symmetry adapted atomic orbitals do.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The symmetric combination—the bonding orbital—is lower in energy than the basis orbitals, and the antisymmetric combination—the antibonding orbital—is higher.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Unlike H2, with two valence electrons, He2 has four in its neutral ground state.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Two electrons fill the lower-energy bonding orbital, σg(1s), while the remaining two fill the higher-energy antibonding orbital, σu*(1s).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Thus, the resulting electron density around the molecule does not support the formation of a bond between the two atoms; without a stable bond holding the atoms together, the molecule would not be expected to exist.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Another way of looking at it is that there are two bonding electrons and two antibonding electrons; therefore, the bond order is 0 and no bond exists (the molecule has one bound state supported by the Van der Waals potential).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Dilithium Li2 is formed from the overlap of the 1s and 2s atomic orbitals (the basis set) of two Li atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Each Li atom contributes three electrons for bonding interactions, and the six electrons fill the three MOs of lowest energy, σg(1s), σu*(1s), and σg(2s).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Using the equation for bond order, it is found that dilithium has a bond order of one, a single bond.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Considering a hypothetical molecule of He2, since the basis set of atomic orbitals is the same as in the case of H2, we find that both the bonding and antibonding orbitals are filled, so there is no energy advantage to the pair.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] HeH would have a slight energy advantage, but not as much as H2 + 2 He, so the molecule is very unstable and exists only briefly before decomposing into hydrogen and helium.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In general, we find that atoms such as He that have full energy shells rarely bond with other atoms.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Except for short-lived Van der Waals complexes, there are very few noble gas compounds known.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] While MOs for homonuclear diatomic molecules contain equal contributions from each interacting atomic orbital, MOs for heteronuclear diatomics contain different atomic orbital contributions.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Orbital interactions to produce bonding or antibonding orbitals in heteronuclear diatomics occur if there is sufficient overlap between atomic orbitals as determined by their symmetries and similarity in orbital energies.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] In hydrogen fluoride HF overlap between the H 1s and F 2s orbitals is allowed by symmetry but the difference in energy between the two atomic orbitals prevents them from interacting to create a molecular orbital.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Overlap between the H 1s and F 2pz orbitals is also symmetry allowed, and these two atomic orbitals have a small energy separation.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Thus, they interact, leading to creation of σ and σ* MOs and a molecule with a bond order of 1.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Since HF is a non-centrosymmetric molecule, the symmetry labels g and u do not apply to its molecular orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] To obtain quantitative values for the molecular energy levels, one needs to have molecular orbitals that are such that the configuration interaction (CI) expansion converges fast towards the full CI limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The most common method to obtain such functions is the Hartree–Fock method, which expresses the molecular orbitals as eigenfunctions of the Fock operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] One usually solves this problem by expanding the molecular orbitals as linear combinations of Gaussian functions centered on the atomic nuclei (see linear combination of atomic orbitals and basis set (chemistry)).
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] The equation for the coefficients of these linear combinations is a generalized eigenvalue equation known as the Roothaan equations, which are in fact a particular representation of the Hartree–Fock equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] There are a number of programs in which quantum chemical calculations of MOs can be performed, including Spartan.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Simple accounts often suggest that experimental molecular orbital energies can be obtained by the methods of ultra-violet photoelectron spectroscopy for valence orbitals and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy for core orbitals.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] This, however, is incorrect as these experiments measure the ionization energy, the difference in energy between the molecule and one of the ions resulting from the removal of one electron.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] Ionization energies are linked approximately to orbital energies by Koopmans' theorem.
[src:computational-chemistry/molecular-orbital] While the agreement between these two values can be close for some molecules, it can be very poor in other cases.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The **Schrödinger equation** is a partial differential equation that governs the wave function of a non-relativistic quantum-mechanical system.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Its discovery was a significant landmark in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It is named after Erwin Schrödinger, an Austrian physicist, who postulated the equation in 1925 and published it in 1926, forming the basis for the work that resulted in his Nobel Prize in Physics in 1933.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Conceptually, the Schrödinger equation is the quantum counterpart of Newton's second law in classical mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Given a set of known initial conditions, Newton's second law makes a mathematical prediction as to what path a given physical system will take over time.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation gives the evolution over time of the wave function, the quantum-mechanical characterization of an isolated physical system.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The equation was postulated by Schrödinger based on a postulate of Louis de Broglie that all matter has an associated matter wave.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The equation predicted bound states of the atom in agreement with experimental observations.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is not the only way to study quantum mechanical systems and make predictions.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Other formulations of quantum mechanics include matrix mechanics, introduced by Werner Heisenberg, and the path integral formulation, developed chiefly by Richard Feynman.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] When these approaches are compared, the use of the Schrödinger equation is sometimes called "wave mechanics".
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The equation given by Schrödinger is nonrelativistic because it contains a first derivative in time and a second derivative in space, and therefore space and time are not on equal footing.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Paul Dirac incorporated special relativity and quantum mechanics into a single formulation that simplifies to the Schrödinger equation in the non-relativistic limit.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is the Dirac equation, which contains a single derivative in both space and time.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Another partial differential equation, the Klein–Gordon equation, led to a problem with probability density even though it was a relativistic wave equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The probability density could be negative, which is physically unviable.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This was fixed by Dirac by taking the so-called square root of the Klein–Gordon operator and in turn introducing Dirac matrices.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In a modern context, the Klein–Gordon equation describes spin-less particles, while the Dirac equation describes spin-1/2 particles.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Introductory courses on physics or chemistry typically introduce the Schrödinger equation in a way that can be appreciated knowing only the concepts and notations of basic calculus, particularly derivatives with respect to space and time.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The parameter m is the mass of the particle, and $V(x,t)$ is the *potential energy function* that represents the environment in which the particle exists.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The constant i is the imaginary unit, and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant, which has units of action (energy multiplied by time).
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This vector is postulated to be normalized under the Hilbert space's inner product, that is, in Dirac notation it obeys $\langle \psi |\psi \rangle =1$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Physical quantities of interest – position, momentum, energy, spin – are represented by observables, which are self-adjoint operators acting on the Hilbert space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A wave function can be an eigenvector of an observable, in which case it is called an eigenstate, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] More generally, a quantum state will be a linear combination of the eigenstates, known as a quantum superposition.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] More generally, the eigenvalue is degenerate and the probability is given by $\langle \psi |P_{\lambda }|\psi \rangle$ , where $P_{\lambda }$ is the projector onto its associated eigenspace.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A momentum eigenstate would be a perfectly monochromatic wave of infinite extent, which is not square-integrable.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Likewise a position eigenstate would be a Dirac delta distribution, not square-integrable and technically not a function at all.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, neither can belong to the particle's Hilbert space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Physicists sometimes regard these eigenstates, composed of elements outside the Hilbert space, as "generalized eigenvectors".
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] These are used for calculational convenience and do not represent physical states.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The form of the Schrödinger equation depends on the physical situation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] where t is time, $\vert \Psi (t)\rangle$ is the state vector of the quantum system ( $\Psi$ being the Greek letter psi), and ${\hat {H}}$ is an observable, the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The term "Schrödinger equation" can refer to both the general equation, or the specific nonrelativistic version.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The general equation is indeed quite general, used throughout quantum mechanics, for everything from the Dirac equation to quantum field theory, by plugging in diverse expressions for the Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The specific nonrelativistic version is an approximation that yields accurate results in many situations, but only to a certain extent (see relativistic quantum mechanics and relativistic quantum field theory).
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] To apply the Schrödinger equation, write down the Hamiltonian for the system, accounting for the kinetic and potential energies of the particles constituting the system, then insert it into the Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The resulting partial differential equation is solved for the wave function, which contains information about the system.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In practice, the square of the absolute value of the wave function at each point is taken to define a probability density function.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The time-dependent Schrödinger equation described above predicts that wave functions can form standing waves, called stationary states.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] These states are particularly important as their individual study later simplifies the task of solving the time-dependent Schrödinger equation for *any* state.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is only used when the Hamiltonian itself is not dependent on time explicitly.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] However, even in this case the total wave function is dependent on time as explained in the section on linearity below.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In the language of linear algebra, this equation is an eigenvalue equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Therefore, the wave function is an eigenfunction of the Hamiltonian operator with corresponding eigenvalue(s) E .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, the sum can be extended for any number of state vectors.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This property allows superpositions of quantum states to be solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Even more generally, it holds that a general solution to the Schrödinger equation can be found by taking a weighted sum over a basis of states.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A choice often employed is the basis of energy eigenstates, which are solutions of the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Unitarity is a general feature of time evolution under the Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] If the initial state is $|\Psi (0)\rangle$ , then the state at a later time t will be given by $|\Psi (t)\rangle ={\hat {U}}(t)|\Psi (0)\rangle$ for some unitary operator ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Conversely, suppose that ${\hat {U}}(t)$ is a continuous family of unitary operators parameterized by t .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Without loss of generality, the parameterization can be chosen so that ${\hat {U}}(0)$ is the identity operator and that ${\hat {U}}(t/N)^{N}={\hat {U}}(t)$ for any $N>0$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Then ${\hat {U}}(t)$ depends upon the parameter t in such a way that ${\hat {U}}(t)=e^{-i{\hat {G}}t}$ for some self-adjoint operator ${\hat {G}}$ , called the *generator* of the family ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A Hamiltonian is just such a generator (up to the factor of the Planck constant that would be set to 1 in natural units).
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is often presented using quantities varying as functions of position, but as a vector-operator equation it has a valid representation in any arbitrary complete basis of kets in Hilbert space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] As mentioned above, "bases" that lie outside the physical Hilbert space are also employed for calculational purposes.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is illustrated by the *position-space* and *momentum-space* Schrödinger equations for a nonrelativistic, spinless particle.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] When restricted from three dimensions to one, the position-space equation is just the first form of the Schrödinger equation given above.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The relation between position and momentum in quantum mechanics can be appreciated in a single dimension.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Thus, ${\hat {p}}^{2}$ becomes a second derivative, and in three dimensions, the second derivative becomes the Laplacian $\nabla ^{2}$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The canonical commutation relation also implies that the position and momentum operators are Fourier conjugates of each other.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, functions originally defined in terms of their position dependence can be converted to functions of momentum using the Fourier transform.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In solid-state physics, the Schrödinger equation is often written for functions of momentum, as Bloch's theorem ensures the periodic crystal lattice potential couples ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p)$ with ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p+\hbar K)$ for only discrete reciprocal lattice vectors K .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This makes it convenient to solve the momentum-space Schrödinger equation at each point in the Brillouin zone independently of the other points in the Brillouin zone.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is consistent with local probability conservation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It also ensures that a normalized wavefunction remains normalized after time evolution.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In matrix mechanics, this means that the time evolution operator is a unitary operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In contrast to, for example, the Klein Gordon equation, although a redefined inner product of a wavefunction can be time independent, the total volume integral of modulus square of the wavefunction need not be time independent.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Although the factor ${\textstyle {\nabla S}/{m}}$ appears to play the role of velocity, it does not represent velocity at a point since simultaneous measurement of position and velocity violates uncertainty principle.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The spatial part of the full wave function solves the equation $\nabla ^{2}\psi (\mathbf {r} )+{\frac {2m}{\hbar ^{2}}}\left[E-V(\mathbf {r} )\right]\psi (\mathbf {r} )=0,$ where the energy E appears in the phase factor.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This generalizes to any number of particles in any number of dimensions (in a time-independent potential): the standing wave solutions of the time-independent equation are the states with definite energy, instead of a probability distribution of different energies.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In physics, these standing waves are called "stationary states" or "energy eigenstates"; in chemistry they are called "atomic orbitals" or "molecular orbitals".
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Superpositions of energy eigenstates change their properties according to the relative phases between the energy levels.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The energy eigenstates form a basis: any wave function may be written as a sum over the discrete energy states or an integral over continuous energy states, or more generally as an integral over a measure.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is an example of the spectral theorem, and in a finite-dimensional state space it is just a statement of the completeness of the eigenvectors of a Hermitian matrix.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Separation of variables can also be a useful method for the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The particle in a one-dimensional potential energy box is the most mathematically simple example where restraints lead to the quantization of energy levels.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The box is defined as having zero potential energy *inside* a certain region and infinite potential energy *outside*.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] With the differential operator defined by ${\hat {p}}_{x}=-i\hbar {\frac {d}{dx}}$ the previous equation is evocative of the classic kinetic energy analogue, ${\frac {1}{2m}}{\hat {p}}_{x}^{2}=E,$ with state $\psi$ in this case having energy E coincident with the kinetic energy of the particle.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The infinite potential walls of the box determine the values of $C,D,$ and k at $x=0$ and $x=L$ where $\psi$ must be zero.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] At $x=L$ , $\psi (L)=0=C\sin(kL),$ in which C cannot be zero as this would conflict with the postulate that $\psi$ has norm 1.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A finite potential well is the generalization of the infinite potential well problem to potential wells having finite depth.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The finite potential well problem is mathematically more complicated than the infinite particle-in-a-box problem as the wave function is not pinned to zero at the walls of the well.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Instead, the wave function must satisfy more complicated mathematical boundary conditions as it is nonzero in regions outside the well.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Another related problem is that of the rectangular potential barrier, which furnishes a model for the quantum tunneling effect that plays an important role in the performance of modern technologies such as flash memory and scanning tunneling microscopy.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Furthermore, it can be used to describe approximately a wide variety of other systems, including vibrating atoms, molecules, and atoms or ions in lattices, and approximating other potentials near equilibrium points.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It is also the basis of perturbation methods in quantum mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The case $n=0$ is called the ground state, its energy is called the zero-point energy, and the wave function is a Gaussian.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The harmonic oscillator, like the particle in a box, illustrates the generic feature of the Schrödinger equation that the energies of bound eigenstates are discretized.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The negative sign arises in the potential term since the proton and electron are oppositely charged.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The reduced mass in place of the electron mass is used since the electron and proton together orbit each other about a common center of mass, and constitute a two-body problem to solve.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The motion of the electron is of principal interest here, so the equivalent one-body problem is the motion of the electron using the reduced mass.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation for a hydrogen atom can be solved by separation of variables.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In this case, spherical polar coordinates are the most convenient.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Thus, $\psi (r,\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ \Theta (\theta )\ \Phi (\varphi ),$ where *R* are radial functions and $Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ are spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ and order m .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is the only atom for which the Schrödinger equation has been solved exactly.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Multi-electron atoms require approximate methods.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It is typically not possible to solve the Schrödinger equation exactly for situations of physical interest.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Accordingly, approximate solutions are obtained using techniques like variational methods and WKB approximation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It is also common to treat a problem of interest as a small modification to a problem that can be solved exactly, a method known as perturbation theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] One simple way to compare classical to quantum mechanics is to consider the time-evolution of the *expected* position and *expected* momentum, which can then be compared to the time-evolution of the ordinary position and momentum in classical mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The quantum expectation values satisfy the Ehrenfest theorem.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] For a general $V'$ , therefore, quantum mechanics can lead to predictions where expectation values do not mimic the classical behavior.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In the case of the quantum harmonic oscillator, however, $V'$ is linear and this distinction disappears, so that in this very special case, the expected position and expected momentum do exactly follow the classical trajectories.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] For general systems, the best we can hope for is that the expected position and momentum will *approximately* follow the classical trajectories.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] If the wave function is highly concentrated around a point $x_{0}$ , then $V'\left(\left\langle X\right\rangle \right)$ and $\left\langle V'(X)\right\rangle$ will be *almost* the same, since both will be approximately equal to $V'(x_{0})$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In that case, the expected position and expected momentum will remain very close to the classical trajectories, at least for as long as the wave function remains highly localized in position.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Here the generalized coordinates $q_{i}$ for $i=1,2,3$ (used in the context of the HJE) can be set to the position in Cartesian coordinates as $\mathbf {r} =(q_{1},q_{2},q_{3})=(x,y,z)$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Substituting $\Psi ={\sqrt {\rho (\mathbf {r} ,t)}}e^{iS(\mathbf {r} ,t)/\hbar }$ where $\rho$ is the probability density, into the Schrödinger equation and then taking the limit $\hbar \to 0$ in the resulting equation yield the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Wave functions are not always the most convenient way to describe quantum systems and their behavior.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] When the preparation of a system is only imperfectly known, or when the system under investigation is a part of a larger whole, density matrices may be used instead.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A density matrix is a positive semi-definite operator whose trace is equal to 1.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] (The term "density operator" is also used, particularly when the underlying Hilbert space is infinite-dimensional.) The set of all density matrices is convex, and the extreme points are the operators that project onto vectors in the Hilbert space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The density-matrix analogue of the Schrödinger equation for wave functions is $i\hbar {\frac {\partial {\hat {\rho }}}{\partial t}}=[{\hat {H}},{\hat {\rho }}],$ where the brackets denote a commutator.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is variously known as the von Neumann equation, the Liouville–von Neumann equation, or just the Schrödinger equation for density matrices.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Unitary evolution of a density matrix conserves its von Neumann entropy.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The one-particle Schrödinger equation described above is valid only in the nonrelativistic domain.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The effect of a Galilean transformation upon the Schrödinger equation can be creates a phase factor times the wave function, but the probabilities, as calculated via the Born rule, are unchanged.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] But the time coordinate in the Schrödinger equation is not proper time and relativistic effects on mass are absent.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, processes that change particle number are natural in relativity, and so an equation for one particle (or any fixed number thereof) can only be of limited use.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A more general form of the Schrödinger equation that also applies in relativistic situations can be formulated within quantum field theory (QFT), a framework that allows the combination of quantum mechanics with special relativity.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The region in which both simultaneously apply may be described by relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Such descriptions may use time evolution generated by a Hamiltonian operator, as in the Schrödinger functional method.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Attempts to combine quantum physics with special relativity began with building relativistic wave equations from the relativistic energy–momentum relation $E^{2}=(pc)^{2}+\left(m_{0}c^{2}\right)^{2},$ instead of nonrelativistic energy equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Klein–Gordon equation and the Dirac equation are two such equations.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Historically, Dirac obtained the Dirac equation by seeking a differential equation that would be first-order in both time and space, a desirable property for a relativistic theory.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Taking the "square root" of the left-hand side of the Klein–Gordon equation in this way required factorizing it into a product of two operators, which Dirac wrote using 4 × 4 matrices $\alpha _{1},\alpha _{2},\alpha _{3},\beta$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This has again the form of the Schrödinger equation, with the time derivative of the wave function being given by a Hamiltonian operator acting upon the wave function.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Including influences upon the particle requires modifying the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Dirac equation is true for all spin-1⁄2 particles, and the solutions to the equation are 4-component spinor fields with two components corresponding to the particle and the other two for the antiparticle.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] For the Klein–Gordon equation, the general form of the Schrödinger equation is inconvenient to use, and in practice the Hamiltonian is not expressed in an analogous way to the Dirac Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In general, the Hamiltonian to be substituted in the general Schrödinger equation is not just a function of the position and momentum operators (and possibly time), but also of spin matrices.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Also, the solutions to a relativistic wave equation, for a massive particle of spin *s*, are complex-valued 2(2*s* + 1)-component spinor fields.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] As originally formulated, the Dirac equation is an equation for a single quantum particle, just like the single-particle Schrödinger equation with wave function $\Psi (x,t)$ .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This is of limited use in relativistic quantum mechanics, where particle number is not fixed.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Heuristically, this complication can be motivated by noting that mass–energy equivalence implies material particles can be created from energy.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] A common way to address this in QFT is to introduce a Hilbert space where the basis states are labeled by particle number, a so-called Fock space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation can then be formulated for quantum states on this Hilbert space.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] However, because the Schrödinger equation picks out a preferred time axis, the Lorentz invariance of the theory is no longer manifest, and accordingly, the theory is often formulated in other ways.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Following Max Planck's quantization of light (see black-body radiation), Albert Einstein interpreted Planck's quanta to be photons, particles of light, and proposed that the energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency, one of the first signs of wave–particle duality.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Louis de Broglie hypothesized that this is true for all particles, even particles which have mass such as electrons.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] He showed that, assuming that the matter waves propagate along with their particle counterparts, electrons form standing waves, meaning that only certain discrete rotational frequencies about the nucleus of an atom are allowed.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] These quantized orbits correspond to discrete energy levels, and de Broglie reproduced the Bohr model formula for the energy levels.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This approach essentially confined the electron wave in one dimension, along a circular orbit of radius r .
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Lunn at the University of Chicago had used the same argument based on the completion of the relativistic energy–momentum 4-vector to derive what we now call the de Broglie relation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Following up on de Broglie's ideas, physicist Peter Debye made an offhand comment that if particles behaved as waves, they should satisfy some sort of wave equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Inspired by Debye's remark, Schrödinger decided to find a proper 3-dimensional wave equation for the electron.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] By that time Arnold Sommerfeld had refined the Bohr model with relativistic corrections.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] He found the standing waves of this relativistic equation, but the relativistic corrections disagreed with Sommerfeld's formula.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Discouraged, he put away his calculations and secluded himself with a mistress in a mountain cabin in December 1925.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] While at the cabin, Schrödinger decided that his earlier nonrelativistic calculations were novel enough to publish and decided to leave off the problem of relativistic corrections for the future.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Despite the difficulties in solving the differential equation for hydrogen (he had sought help from his friend the mathematician Hermann Weyl) Schrödinger showed that his nonrelativistic version of the wave equation produced the correct spectral energies of hydrogen in a paper published in 1926.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger computed the hydrogen spectral series by treating a hydrogen atom's electron as a wave $\Psi (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ , moving in a potential well V , created by the proton.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This computation accurately reproduced the energy levels of the Bohr model.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation details the behavior of $\Psi$ but says nothing of its *nature*.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger tried to interpret the real part of $\Psi {\frac {\partial \Psi ^{*}}{\partial t}}$ as a charge density, and then revised this proposal, saying in his next paper that the modulus squared of $\Psi$ is a charge density.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This approach was, however, unsuccessful.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In 1926, just a few days after this paper was published, Max Born successfully interpreted $\Psi$ as the probability amplitude, whose modulus squared is equal to probability density.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation provides a way to calculate the wave function of a system and how it changes dynamically in time.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] However, the Schrödinger equation does not directly say *what,* exactly, the wave function is.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The meaning of the Schrödinger equation and how the mathematical entities in it relate to physical reality depends upon the interpretation of quantum mechanics that one adopts.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] In the views often grouped together as the Copenhagen interpretation, a system's wave function is a collection of statistical information about that system.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation relates information about the system at one time to information about it at another.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The wave function changes, according to this school of thought, because new information is available.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The post-measurement wave function generally cannot be known prior to the measurement, but the probabilities for the different possibilities can be calculated using the Born rule.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Other, more recent interpretations of quantum mechanics, such as relational quantum mechanics and QBism, view the Schrödinger equation in a similar way.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger himself suggested in 1952 that the different terms of a superposition evolving under the Schrödinger equation are "not alternatives but all really happen simultaneously".
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This has been interpreted as an early version of Everett's many-worlds interpretation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation, formulated independently in 1956, holds that *all* the possibilities described by quantum theory *simultaneously* occur in a multiverse composed of mostly independent parallel universes.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation removes the axiom of wave function collapse, leaving only continuous evolution under the Schrödinger equation, and so all possible states of the measured system and the measuring apparatus, together with the observer, are present in a real physical quantum superposition.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] While the multiverse is deterministic, we perceive non-deterministic behavior governed by probabilities, because we do not observe the multiverse as a whole, but only one parallel universe at a time.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Exactly how this is supposed to work has been the subject of much debate.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Why should we assign probabilities at all to outcomes that are certain to occur in some worlds, and why should the probabilities be given by the Born rule?
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Several ways to answer these questions in the many-worlds framework have been proposed, but there is no consensus on whether they are successful.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] Bohmian mechanics reformulates quantum mechanics to make it deterministic, at the price of adding a force due to a "quantum potential".
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] It attributes to each physical system not only a wave function but in addition a real position that evolves deterministically under a nonlocal guiding equation.
[src:computational-chemistry/schrödinger-equation] The evolution of a physical system is given at all times by the Schrödinger equation together with the guiding equation.
